{"term":"1956","caseName":"Service v. Dulles","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/407","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 03, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13211","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 407, John S.Service, Petitioner, versus John Foster Dulles, et al.","start":0,"stop":10.851,"duration":10.85},{"text":"Mr. MacGuineas, you may proceed.","start":10.851,"stop":19.901,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":19.901,"stop":23.121,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Counsel's skillful argument of yesterday invested petitioner with an aura of irreproachability which I think is scarcely warranted by the record.","start":23.121,"stop":35.341,"duration":12.22},{"text":"The facts that were before the Secretary of State, when he exercised his discretion to dismiss the petitioner were these.","start":35.341,"stop":45.2,"duration":9.86},{"text":"His counsel indicated, “When petitioner was on assignment with the army as a Foreign Service Officer during the war in China in 1944, it was his practice to prepare the usual Foreign Service reports.”","start":45.2,"stop":60.581,"duration":15.38},{"text":"The original of which was transmitted to the Secretary of State, other copies went to the Army and it was his practice to retain one copy in what he termed his personal file.","start":60.581,"stop":74.146,"duration":13.56},{"text":"The petitioner himself classified many of those reports as either confidential or secret, and that he was authorized to do.","start":74.146,"stop":84.419,"duration":10.27},{"text":"A year later, when petitioner returned to Washington, without making any effort to declassify those reports, without obtaining any clearance from any person in authority in the Secretary in the Department of State, he gave his copies of the Foreign Service reports to Mr. Jaffe.","start":84.419,"stop":112.277,"duration":27.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I -- did I correctly hear you saying that he determined what was and what was not classified?","start":112.277,"stop":118.579,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":118.579,"stop":118.913,"duration":0.33},{"text":"He had the authority in the field --","start":118.913,"stop":120.769,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he determine that?","start":120.769,"stop":121.695,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to classify them on --","start":121.695,"stop":122.46,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Just to be sure I heard that --","start":122.46,"stop":123.774,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":123.774,"stop":124.456,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"While you're on that subject, would you mind stating whether he has the right to declassify as well as classify or is there a procedure for that?","start":124.456,"stop":135.445,"duration":10.99}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- there is no contention that petitioner had the authority to declassify any of the reports.","start":135.445,"stop":142.463,"duration":7.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is it a classification for him to say confidential?","start":142.463,"stop":148.033,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, at that time --","start":148.033,"stop":149.571,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and --","start":149.571,"stop":150.196,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and secret.","start":150.196,"stop":150.821,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And he has no authority beyond that?","start":150.821,"stop":153.402,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":153.402,"stop":154.498,"duration":1.1},{"text":"He is the --","start":154.498,"stop":154.619,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand you to say that the John Smith today has -- has the legal right to regard a document, stamp on it or treat it as classified or not classified, not subject to restriction today, he can do that.","start":154.619,"stop":171.429,"duration":16.81}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":171.429,"stop":171.542,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But having that power tomorrow he can say, \"Looking away, I think it's silly.\"","start":171.542,"stop":175.043,"duration":3.5},{"text":"This was in yesterday's New York Times, why should I keep this classified.","start":175.043,"stop":178.707,"duration":3.66},{"text":"Is that what I understood you to say?","start":178.707,"stop":179.312,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what -- what I said was it must be remembered that petitioner was operating in time of war in a field of military operations.","start":179.312,"stop":189.432,"duration":10.12},{"text":"He at that time was the only one who could append the classification of those reports.","start":189.432,"stop":195.57,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, I understood you?","start":195.57,"stop":196.502,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":196.502,"stop":197.107,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But he couldn't the next day say, “This is a -- announced these over the radio and I'm not going to be silly and call this classified.”","start":197.107,"stop":203.663,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he could not.","start":203.663,"stop":204.599,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He could not do that.","start":204.599,"stop":205.244,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"He could not declassify the documents himself.","start":205.244,"stop":207.664,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Although it's all over the world.","start":207.664,"stop":209.312,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":209.312,"stop":209.355,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just asking for a fact.","start":209.355,"stop":210.799,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":210.799,"stop":211.482,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the word --","start":211.482,"stop":211.766,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that is correct.","start":211.766,"stop":212.822,"duration":1.06},{"text":"He did not have the authority --","start":212.822,"stop":213.635,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":213.635,"stop":214.19,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of declassification.","start":214.19,"stop":214.424,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not asking you to justify what seems to me silly, if I may say so, but I just want to know what the fact is, whether he has power ab initio to say, “This is not a classifiable material.”","start":214.424,"stop":225.674,"duration":11.25},{"text":"This is not classified material, but once having made a decision, he's like the House of Laws, he can't change it.","start":225.674,"stop":231.888,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because that function is vested in higher authority in the Department of State.","start":231.888,"stop":235.98,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I should think the initial function of whether it is or it isn't seems to me at least as -- as big a function as to say I was wrong yesterday or foolish yesterday.","start":235.98,"stop":243.695,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But the exigencies of the situation made it necessary that that function be vested to him.","start":243.695,"stop":247.045,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Anyhow, you're not defending that.","start":247.045,"stop":248.59,"duration":1.55},{"text":"I just want to know what the fact is.","start":248.59,"stop":249.847,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. MacGuineas, what's the significance of Mr. Rhett's statement to us yesterday that Mr. Service brought back his copies with permission?","start":249.847,"stop":259.784,"duration":9.94},{"text":"From -- from whom did he have that permission?","start":259.784,"stop":263.134,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I do not contend that he did not have the right.","start":263.134,"stop":266.663,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm asking --","start":266.663,"stop":267.689,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":267.689,"stop":267.819,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who gave him that permission?","start":267.819,"stop":269.234,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not believe that the record explicitly shows.","start":269.234,"stop":271.845,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Government agrees that he did have permission to bring those back with him from China?","start":271.845,"stop":276.953,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":276.953,"stop":277.164,"duration":0.21},{"text":"We do not contest that.","start":277.164,"stop":279.654,"duration":2.49},{"text":"What the point is what he did with them after he got them back.","start":279.654,"stop":282.924,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's the -- if -- if he was entitled to keep them, what the permission contemplate that they were then his own personal papers?","start":282.924,"stop":291.212,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are many officers in the Government who have the right of possession of classified documents.","start":291.212,"stop":298.004,"duration":6.79},{"text":"But the question is, to what extent may that person disseminate those documents to other persons to have no right of possession of classified documents?","start":298.004,"stop":307.106,"duration":9.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. MacGuineas, I don't want to take your time but you surprise me a little bit.","start":307.106,"stop":310.961,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Of course, there must be officers since the Government is in obstruction.","start":310.961,"stop":314.274,"duration":3.31},{"text":"There must be human beings who are the Government who have -- technically speaking, the possession of classified material.","start":314.274,"stop":321.529,"duration":7.25},{"text":"But I think a good deal would have to be said pro and con whether classified materials can be deemed to be the private -- the private property of a person.","start":321.529,"stop":333.947,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not --","start":333.947,"stop":334.258,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Either while he's still in the Government or after he leaves the Government.","start":334.258,"stop":336.748,"duration":2.49},{"text":"It's one of the most troubling of problems in the disposition of the confidential papers.","start":336.748,"stop":341.743,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not I who is advancing the contention that he had the right to retain them.","start":341.743,"stop":347.089,"duration":5.35},{"text":"I -- that is petitioner's contention.","start":347.089,"stop":348.185,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I merely -- your answer to Justice Brennan's question --","start":348.185,"stop":350.853,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":350.853,"stop":351.295,"duration":0.44},{"text":"And I said we do not take issue with it under these circumstances.","start":351.295,"stop":354.869,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The record does not disclose any determination by the Secretary of State that he did not have the right to retain possession of the copies.","start":354.869,"stop":364.756,"duration":9.89},{"text":"That's all I'm saying.","start":364.756,"stop":366.632,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I ask this?","start":366.632,"stop":369.714,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Does the Government recognize or -- or is it a fact that a man -- a man can keep copies of classified material, not only the -- the confidential documents but those that are -- that are of higher grades and classification.","start":369.714,"stop":386.805,"duration":17.09},{"text":"Can he keep a copy for -- for himself under your regulations?","start":386.805,"stop":391.028,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think one can generalize about that.","start":391.028,"stop":393.498,"duration":2.47},{"text":"It might depend upon the person.","start":393.498,"stop":395.417,"duration":1.92},{"text":"It might depend upon the category of the document.","start":395.417,"stop":400.044,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what -- what is there to determine, what he can keep and what he can't keep?","start":400.044,"stop":403.588,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Is there any rule on it or --","start":403.588,"stop":406.299,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"There is nothing in this record that explicitly states whether petitioner was entitled to retain these copies.","start":406.299,"stop":415.61,"duration":9.31},{"text":"I think it must be recognized that when a man in petitioner's position is operating in China in the middle of the war that -- what he does not always proceed with strict formality.","start":415.61,"stop":432.037,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you're not questioning as I understood your answer to Justice Brennan, you are not questioning that control over (a) set of these documents, copies of these documents by Service unlike other documents that he had was in and of itself an impropriety of this kind.","start":432.037,"stop":456.998,"duration":24.96}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we make no such assertion.","start":456.998,"stop":459.007,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not -- without regard to whether they were marked confidential or -- or secret.","start":459.007,"stop":464.433,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":464.433,"stop":465.247,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":465.247,"stop":466.464,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, when petitioner, upon his return to the United States, decided that he would go to Mr. Jaffe's hotel room at the Statler, here in Washington.","start":466.464,"stop":481.564,"duration":15.1},{"text":"He had not known Jaffe previously.","start":481.564,"stop":485.729,"duration":4.16},{"text":"And yet, on that same day, it appears that he made inquiry of a mutual acquaintance of himself in Jaffe as to whether or not Jaffe was a communist.","start":485.729,"stop":500.005,"duration":14.28},{"text":"And the reply that he received was not very assuring.","start":500.005,"stop":503.857,"duration":3.85},{"text":"The reply in effect was, “I don't think he is but he is very sympathetic.”","start":503.857,"stop":511.342,"duration":7.48},{"text":"And later on, petitioner obviously had strong reservations about the character of Mr. Jaffe because he asked another person who was himself admittedly a former communist as to whether Jaffe was a communist.","start":511.342,"stop":528.095,"duration":16.75},{"text":"And this other person replied, \"No, he is not but he is bad medicine.\"","start":528.095,"stop":535.932,"duration":7.84},{"text":"Now, under those circumstances, petitioner loans to Jaffe several copies of his classified documents without any further control over them whatever, and Jaffe takes them off to New York.","start":535.932,"stop":553.029,"duration":17.1},{"text":"He does with them as he pleases, and a week or so later, petitioner meets with Jaffe in New York and recovers possession of the reports.","start":553.029,"stop":563.775,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. MacGuineas, is it relevant to the issues in this case for me to be curious about the circumstances that led Service to have association, the initial to have this meeting with Jaffe.","start":563.775,"stop":580.6,"duration":16.83},{"text":"Is it relevant to the issues for me to have that curiosity satisfied or is it irrelevant?","start":580.6,"stop":587.817,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Does it appear in the record?","start":587.817,"stop":589.505,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":589.505,"stop":590.017,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the purposes for which in his mind, the purposes for which if that's relevant and that's in the record, then, I think you ought to know if it isn't -- if it's not in the record, even though relevant and I don't ask for the answer.","start":590.017,"stop":605.217,"duration":15.2}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that counsel made a fair statement yesterday of the background which led up to petitioner becoming introduced to Jaffe, and I take no exception to what he said as to that.","start":605.217,"stop":618.739,"duration":13.52},{"text":"I'm merely pointing out --","start":618.739,"stop":620.404,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that he didn't go and seek out Jaffe, right?","start":620.404,"stop":624.386,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":624.386,"stop":624.667,"duration":0.28},{"text":"He did not -- he did not.","start":624.667,"stop":627.027,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"This wasn't -- this wasn't doing what is -- it is to me so shocking, has been for long, Government by leakage.","start":627.027,"stop":634.435,"duration":7.41},{"text":"This isn't the case where appellant sold out a journalist to get some stuff into this circulation, is it?","start":634.435,"stop":639.955,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the leakage -- there was a leakage (Voice Overlap) --","start":639.955,"stop":641.934,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I mean this isn't the case of an official of a State Department and as a basis under -- on the strength to which he was later dismissed.","start":641.934,"stop":650.408,"duration":8.47},{"text":"This isn't a case of an official of the State Department having views which he thinks is -- are important for the public interest to be out at the -- in the stream of publicity in which he sought out a newspaperman and gave it to him, is it?","start":650.408,"stop":664.425,"duration":14.02}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Petitioner did not take the initiative --","start":664.425,"stop":666.153,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":666.153,"stop":666.584,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in meeting Jaffe.","start":666.584,"stop":671.75,"duration":5.17},{"text":"Well, I -- I'm really pointing out that those were facts which were before the Secretary of State when he formed his judgment as to whether or not petitioner should be retained as a Foreign Service officer.","start":671.75,"stop":686.739,"duration":14.99},{"text":"Now, I'm not sure whether it was made plain from the argument yesterday, that in so far as the Secretary of State exercised his purported authority to dismiss Jaffe under the Loyalty Program, that is Executive Order No.9835.","start":686.739,"stop":706.527,"duration":19.79},{"text":"The petitioner has already received the relief to which he was entitled.","start":706.527,"stop":712.297,"duration":5.77},{"text":"When this case was heard in the District Court, this Court's opinion in Peters v.Hobby had just come down.","start":712.297,"stop":720.395,"duration":8.1},{"text":"That of course established that the handling of this case by the Loyalty Review Board in the Civil Service Commission was beyond its jurisdiction.","start":720.395,"stop":731.982,"duration":11.59},{"text":"And the District Court recognized that and he said that “the opinion of the Review Board is a nullity and I will order the Civil Service Commission to expunge the opinion from the record,' which is precisely the relief which this Court granted in Peters versus Hobby.","start":731.982,"stop":748.566,"duration":16.58},{"text":"So, to us, petitioner's present contention and I may say that that relief was granted without objection on the part of the Government.","start":748.566,"stop":758.327,"duration":9.76},{"text":"Petitioner's present contention as to the adequacy or the vise of the proceedings before the Loyalty Review Board as an exercise of purported authority under 9835 is simply bidding a dead horse that's not in this case.","start":758.327,"stop":776.272,"duration":17.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Except in so far as that nullity affected the determination of the Secretary.","start":776.272,"stop":782.902,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":782.902,"stop":783.143,"duration":0.24},{"text":"Now, that's the next thing.","start":783.143,"stop":784.37,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't -- you can't make a fact nullity.","start":784.37,"stop":786.319,"duration":1.95},{"text":"The legal counsels may be a nullity but the fact may not.","start":786.319,"stop":789.09,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's precisely my point of view which I hope to develop in a moment.","start":789.09,"stop":792.962,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, may I ask one more -- one more question.","start":792.962,"stop":796.265,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Were these facts concerning with conduct of -- of the petitioner that you have outlined known to the Department at the time that he was cleared on these successive occasions?","start":796.265,"stop":809.62,"duration":13.36}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Most of these facts were developed at the hearings before the State Department Board and the conclusion of the State Department Board was this.","start":809.62,"stop":819.183,"duration":9.56},{"text":"They said, “Petitioner has been guilty of serious indiscretions in giving these classified reports to Jaffe without making a proper investigation of his character.","start":819.183,"stop":830.854,"duration":11.67},{"text":"And furthermore, petitioner has been guilty of a breach of the Department's regulations.”","start":830.854,"stop":836.477,"duration":5.62},{"text":"“But,” said the State Department Board, “in our opinion, he has now learned his lesson.","start":836.477,"stop":843.107,"duration":6.63},{"text":"And therefore, will not in the future be a security risk.","start":843.107,"stop":846.967,"duration":3.86},{"text":"And therefore, we recommend that the Secretary not find that he be a security risk.”","start":846.967,"stop":853.316,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's the sum in substance of the -- of their findings on each of the occasions when they found him not to be a security risk.","start":853.316,"stop":861.856,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that is the -- that is the only finding as to the less proceeding.","start":861.856,"stop":868.99,"duration":7.13},{"text":"The -- the record does not disclose that the -- that the State Department Board wrote any opinion or made specific finds as to the prior investigations.","start":868.99,"stop":878.17,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But the facts were before them though.","start":878.17,"stop":880.655,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":880.655,"stop":881.641,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You say in connection.","start":881.641,"stop":882.125,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because there was no elaborate hearing on this last investigation before the State Department Board at which petitioner testified at great length and other people testified.","start":882.125,"stop":895.077,"duration":12.95},{"text":"And I may say that the Secretary has before him one other fact and that was the curious contrast between petitioner's dealings with Jaffe and his dealings with Brooks Atkinson who is a reporter of the New York Times.","start":895.077,"stop":912.424,"duration":17.35},{"text":"Mr. Atkinson testified before the State Department Board on behalf of the petitioner and he said in effect, “I have always found petitioner exceedingly stroked of us about not giving out confidential material.","start":912.424,"stop":928.256,"duration":15.83},{"text":"He has always refused to let me see any classified material.”","start":928.256,"stop":933.733,"duration":5.48},{"text":"And yet, by contrast, when petitioner is dealing with Jaffe, a man whose reputation was doubtfully in his own mind, he did not have any such reservations or scruple.","start":933.733,"stop":945.668,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you about dates.","start":945.668,"stop":948.068,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Mr. Brooks Atkinson, his chief occupation is not being a political reporter.","start":948.068,"stop":951.92,"duration":3.85},{"text":"When -- when did he -- he did go to China as reported from there.","start":951.92,"stop":957.51,"duration":5.59},{"text":"But this Jaffe episode is what the -- what he wants?","start":957.51,"stop":962.127,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":962.127,"stop":962.782,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When is that?","start":962.782,"stop":963.668,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"The Jaffe episode is in 1945.","start":963.668,"stop":965.717,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"1945.","start":965.717,"stop":966.282,"duration":0.57},{"text":"And when was the Brooks Atkinson episode?","start":966.282,"stop":968.331,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Brooks Atkinson testified thereafter at the hearing before the State Department Board in 1950 --","start":968.331,"stop":974.886,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I follow that.","start":974.886,"stop":975.548,"duration":0.66},{"text":"I understand that, but -- but his testimony -- your argument is that he was caught putting or coming to Jaffe, but withdrawing in reticent, vis-à-vis Atkinson.","start":975.548,"stop":989.463,"duration":13.91},{"text":"What I want to know is when did Atkinson have occasioned to have these conversations with -- with --","start":989.463,"stop":996.265,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":996.265,"stop":996.626,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Peters, with Service?","start":996.626,"stop":998.111,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Was it contemporaneous with his indiscretion of Service or was it later by the time when he may have learned his lesson?","start":998.111,"stop":1008.932,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1008.932,"stop":1009.356,"duration":0.42},{"text":"They would have had to, have been earlier because Atkinson gave this testimony before the State Department Board had made its ruling in the case.","start":1009.356,"stop":1019.38,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When was that?","start":1019.38,"stop":1020.326,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That was in 1950.","start":1020.326,"stop":1022.325,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well, I'm suggesting that the Jaffe episode was 1945 and the fact that he was discrete with Atkinson in 1948 wouldn't show that he sought out Jaffe as a good fellow to leak to but was held at from Atkinson.","start":1022.325,"stop":1037.405,"duration":15.08}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I appreciate Your Honor's point now.","start":1037.405,"stop":1039.534,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Well, as far as the material that was before the Secretary of State when he made his decision, the opinion of the Review Board does not state the time or times at which Atkinson had communication with petitioner.","start":1039.534,"stop":1054.313,"duration":14.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I suggest that that's vital in order to draw any inference, discreditable or adverse to Service that later -- that at a later time, he said, \"Oh, no, I'm not even going to give it to so estimable on that as Mr. Atkinson.\"","start":1054.313,"stop":1068.28,"duration":13.97},{"text":"And if my memory isn't at fault, I think Atkinson is trying to ensure his labor.","start":1068.28,"stop":1072.904,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I confess that I have no personal knowledge of that.","start":1072.904,"stop":1075.515,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. MacGuineas, his -- in his relations with Mr. Atkinson, was Mr. Atkinson talking about the very same papers that he had turned over to him.","start":1075.515,"stop":1084.547,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, no.","start":1084.547,"stop":1085.503,"duration":0.96},{"text":"His general course of -- of dealing with petitioner as a Foreign Service officer in one hand and Atkinson at New York Times reporter on the other.","start":1085.503,"stop":1094.523,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's clear that they were not the very same papers.","start":1094.523,"stop":1097.131,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No indication that he was (Voice Overlap) --","start":1097.131,"stop":1098.265,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, was there anything -- anything in Mr. Service's own testimony or otherwise to indicate Mr. Service's idea, whether he thought these copies were in fact still classified at the time he turned them over to Jaffe?","start":1098.265,"stop":1111.479,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Service in his testimony expressed his opinion that the material that was contained in these reports was such, as he might legitimately give by way of background information to members of the press.","start":1111.479,"stop":1127.894,"duration":16.41},{"text":"But petitioner did not contend that he had under the State Department's regulations, any authority to actually turn over these testified documents to Jaffe or anybody else.","start":1127.894,"stop":1140.332,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if he -- I would suppose so if his honest conviction was if there were papers he could turn over to the press.","start":1140.332,"stop":1147.445,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1147.445,"stop":1147.465,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He could not have thought that they were classified.","start":1147.465,"stop":1149.822,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm sorry.","start":1149.822,"stop":1150.414,"duration":0.59},{"text":"I did not mean to say that he thought he could turn the papers over to the press.","start":1150.414,"stop":1154.429,"duration":4.02},{"text":"He could convey to the press as background information, the substance of the material that was stated in his reports.","start":1154.429,"stop":1164.661,"duration":10.23},{"text":"But that is of course a different matter from having authority to turn over the classified document itself.","start":1164.661,"stop":1170.942,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the difference on effect?","start":1170.942,"stop":1173.001,"duration":2.06},{"text":"Do, I --","start":1173.001,"stop":1173.382,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1173.382,"stop":1173.392,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- understand you to say that it will be something wrong to tell somebody everything in the paper?","start":1173.392,"stop":1177.887,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1177.887,"stop":1178.793,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"There'll be nothing wrong in that and yet it'll be all right, it'll be all wrong to turn over the paper?","start":1178.793,"stop":1185.737,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"A man who -- also, the Government who has some authority to give information to the press may under some circumstances be authorized to discuss with appropriate discretion and rephrasing the substance of matters that may be contained in classified documents, but that is by no means the same as turning over the classified document itself and say, \"here it is.\"","start":1185.737,"stop":1217.192,"duration":31.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"For them to look at?","start":1217.192,"stop":1218.225,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because the person who was given that authority is assumed to have the discretion that he can convey communications about that subject matter by way of paraphrase or in such of a way.","start":1218.225,"stop":1231.13,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does he have to paraphrase it?","start":1231.13,"stop":1232.615,"duration":1.48},{"text":"He couldn't give him the exact language.","start":1232.615,"stop":1234.881,"duration":2.27},{"text":"The paraphrases would be alright.","start":1234.881,"stop":1236.669,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think that if he -- if he literally read the report to the man that that would be a breach of security regulations.","start":1236.669,"stop":1242.786,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"He paraphrased it and he told him precisely the same thing in different words.","start":1242.786,"stop":1246.728,"duration":3.94},{"text":"That would be all right.","start":1246.728,"stop":1247.48,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"It all depends.","start":1247.48,"stop":1249.356,"duration":1.88},{"text":"A paraphrase is not precisely the same thing by definition.","start":1249.356,"stop":1252.905,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood you to say the substance of it.","start":1252.905,"stop":1255.058,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":1255.058,"stop":1255.85,"duration":0.79},{"text":"But -- but the way the thing is presented, the sources of the information, all of those things may be relevant which cannot be revealed without breaching security.","start":1255.85,"stop":1265.373,"duration":9.52},{"text":"And yet, the essence of the matter maybe able to be presented in a way --","start":1265.373,"stop":1269.927,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all right.","start":1269.927,"stop":1270.579,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which does not breach security.","start":1270.579,"stop":1271.682,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all right if it's the substance of phase not seen.","start":1271.682,"stop":1275.345,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That may well be solved, yes.","start":1275.345,"stop":1277.304,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what reason did Service give?","start":1277.304,"stop":1280.577,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Well, believing that he committed no impropriety in turning these papers over to Jaffe.","start":1280.577,"stop":1284.482,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because when Service was in China, which was of course Chungking in 1944 was a very different atmosphere from Washington, D.C.in 1945.","start":1284.482,"stop":1296.105,"duration":11.62},{"text":"He was on his own so to speak.","start":1296.105,"stop":1298.254,"duration":2.15},{"text":"He was the political advisor of General Stilwell in China.","start":1298.254,"stop":1303.259,"duration":5.01},{"text":"As such, Service considered that he have the right within proper limits of security to discuss with the press the Chinese situation.","start":1303.259,"stop":1314.961,"duration":11.7},{"text":"And he considered, so he testified at least that he has that right to carry that over into Washington when he was back here and that what he did to Jaffe fell within what he considered that right.","start":1314.961,"stop":1331.302,"duration":16.34},{"text":"Although, I say I -- I do not consider that anything at the record that supports the view that even petitioner considered that he have the right to turn over the physical classified documents to anybody.","start":1331.302,"stop":1342.954,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say all that was developing for the Loyalty Board, all for the --","start":1342.954,"stop":1346.598,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"This -- this was developed initially before the State Department Board, and then in supplementary fashion, before the Loyalty Review Board which held its own hearing.","start":1346.598,"stop":1358.051,"duration":11.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you must choose the way you argue the case of course.","start":1358.051,"stop":1362.274,"duration":4.22},{"text":"But Mr. Atkinson says within explicitness which I should think carries weight in the case, not only as an ex Secretary of State or Secretary of State for the lawyer with his sense of relevance.","start":1362.274,"stop":1375.358,"duration":13.08},{"text":"I did not read the testimony taken in the proceeding to Mr. Service's case before the Loyalty Review Board of the Civil Service Commission.","start":1375.358,"stop":1385.554,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":1385.554,"stop":1385.775,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to me.","start":1385.775,"stop":1386.249,"duration":0.47},{"text":"That's rather striking.","start":1386.249,"stop":1388.205,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I can't tell, asking myself, why should a lawyer, let alone, the Secretary of State make such a statement being a lawyer of Mr. Acheson's understanding of what is relevant and what isn't relevant.","start":1388.205,"stop":1400.991,"duration":12.79},{"text":"A complete disavow that even looked at his testimony.","start":1400.991,"stop":1404.174,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that leads us into what we consider the real issue in the case.","start":1404.174,"stop":1409.443,"duration":5.27},{"text":"And if I may, by way of introduction, give the legal situation as it existed at the time that Mr. Acheson made his determination.","start":1409.443,"stop":1418.62,"duration":9.18},{"text":"At that time, there were four statutes and one executive order, which gave Government employees a different classes, certain procedural protections with respect to their removal.","start":1418.62,"stop":1432.978,"duration":14.36},{"text":"There was, of course, the Civil Service Act which covered employees in the classified Civil Service who might be removed to promote the efficiency of the service.","start":1432.978,"stop":1443.743,"duration":10.76},{"text":"There was the Veterans' Preference Act, which gave similar protection to veterans in the Service.","start":1443.743,"stop":1451.172,"duration":7.43},{"text":"There was the Foreign Service Act, which gave Foreign Service officers such as petitioner, a procedural protection of not being dismissed except pursuant to a hearing before a Board of Foreign Service officers.","start":1451.172,"stop":1467.578,"duration":16.41},{"text":"There was, in addition, the Act of August 26, 1950, which this Court construed in Cole versus Young which authorized a dismissal in accordance with prescribed procedure of any employee in the interest of the national security.","start":1467.578,"stop":1484.956,"duration":17.38},{"text":"And finally, there was Executive Order No.9835 as amended which prescribed procedure for the handling of cases of doubtful loyalty.","start":1484.956,"stop":1496.254,"duration":11.3},{"text":"Now, with all those procedures report, Congress, in the Appropriations Act for the State Department gave to the Secretary of State in these words, “The absolute discretion not withstanding the provisions of any other law to dismiss any officer or employee of the Department of State whenever he might deem not necessary or advisable in the interest of the United States.”","start":1496.254,"stop":1530.138,"duration":33.88},{"text":"Now, to us, Congress by that simply wiped out all the law with respect to procedural protection in the dismissal of employees in the Department of State.","start":1530.138,"stop":1545.16,"duration":15.02},{"text":"It left those employees, strictly employees at will at the pleasure, if you please, of the Secretary of State.","start":1545.16,"stop":1554.773,"duration":9.61},{"text":"Now, that of course is not really so remarkable.","start":1554.773,"stop":1559.063,"duration":4.29},{"text":"For a hundred years in our Government, essentially, all employees in the executive branch held tenure or rather lack of tenure solely at the pleasure of the superior officer, the President or the officers under him.","start":1559.063,"stop":1578.028,"duration":18.96},{"text":"And indeed, today, the highest level of officials in the executive branch, hold office solely at the will, solely at the pleasure of the President.","start":1578.028,"stop":1591.602,"duration":13.57},{"text":"By this statute, as we see it, the relationship which obtained between Foreign Service officers and the Secretary of State was exactly as that which obtains between the President and the Secretary of State himself.","start":1591.602,"stop":1608.407,"duration":16.8},{"text":"In other words, the President at any time is free to say to the Secretary of State, \"You're doing a fine job but you don't get along with the press or you don't get along with Appropriations Committee, so you've got to go,\" and that's it, no notice, no charges, no proceeding.","start":1608.407,"stop":1628.132,"duration":19.73},{"text":"And by this statute, the Foreign Service officers were placed in exactly that situation.","start":1628.132,"stop":1636.088,"duration":7.96},{"text":"So --","start":1636.088,"stop":1637.355,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does the -- does the constitution or any statute say that the President has the discretion to do that or that he has the power to do that?","start":1637.355,"stop":1646.647,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the President's right to do that is derived from the -- his constitutional duty to execute the laws and implied in that, of course, is that if he is to execute the laws, he must have complete control over the executive personnel whom he needs to discharge that function.","start":1646.647,"stop":1668.218,"duration":21.57},{"text":"And hence, except as Congress may otherwise validly provide with respect to inferior officers of the Government, all the executive officers and employees hold their position solely at the pleasure of their superior officer.","start":1668.218,"stop":1685.725,"duration":17.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But to do you read the words \"absolute discretion\" as being synonymous with absolute power?","start":1685.725,"stop":1692.435,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1692.435,"stop":1693.378,"duration":0.94},{"text":"In other --","start":1693.378,"stop":1693.391,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And you make no distinction at all between the two?","start":1693.391,"stop":1696.43,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I find it hard to conceive of a case which could turn on -- on a distinction between those two words.","start":1696.43,"stop":1704.952,"duration":8.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps suppose the -- suppose in this case, the -- the Secretary of State said that instead of saying what he did, \"I -- I relieve this man from -- from duty because he's a Republican.\"","start":1704.952,"stop":1718.377,"duration":13.42}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No question about his authority to do that in my opinion.","start":1718.377,"stop":1720.496,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"He could do it.","start":1720.496,"stop":1721.329,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":1721.329,"stop":1722.646,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What of the words, \"absolute discretion?\"","start":1722.646,"stop":1724.675,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolute means absolute and for a hundred years --","start":1724.675,"stop":1726.44,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And for either use, any other thing -- any other thing that he wanted whether it was -- was right, whether it was wholesome or whether or not?","start":1726.44,"stop":1734.566,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the point is that Congress said, \"We're leaving it to you, Mr. Secretary and nobody else could decide what's the right thing to do.","start":1734.566,"stop":1742.99,"duration":8.42},{"text":"We want you to make that decision and we want that to be made not subject to review by any other organ of Government.\"","start":1742.99,"stop":1750.605,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understood you, Mr. MacGuineas, you said there were four ways of disposing.","start":1750.605,"stop":1755.894,"duration":5.29},{"text":"And then, on top of that or undercutting at all, Congress said in your interpretation to the Secretary of State, “You can fire a fellow for any reason you choose.”","start":1755.894,"stop":1766.3,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1766.3,"stop":1766.644,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But there was these other four, is that right?","start":1766.644,"stop":1769.011,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but at the same time, Congress said, “notwithstanding the provisions --","start":1769.011,"stop":1771.669,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, but there were --","start":1771.669,"stop":1772.231,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of any other law.”","start":1772.231,"stop":1772.796,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There were outstanding four procedures, all of which, the Secretary of State could disregard, is that right?","start":1772.796,"stop":1779.439,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Under this statute, yes.","start":1779.439,"stop":1780.525,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under this statute.","start":1780.525,"stop":1781.328,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1781.328,"stop":1781.451,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, therefore, I take it your argument is that if he wanted to fire Service because he -- it's a safe thing to do, a wise thing to do, he could have done it without saying anything.","start":1781.451,"stop":1792.541,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No question about that.","start":1792.541,"stop":1793.885,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But in as much as there were four -- four procedures outstanding, and the Secretary chose in fact to rely on one of the four, he wouldn't be within the framework of the one he chose but the Government comes here and they could come here and does come here and say, “Although he could have chosen any of the four and although for purposes of the moment, he did choose one of the four.","start":1793.885,"stop":1820.533,"duration":26.65},{"text":"He could have chosen the one that let them free entirely on credits and debits to be supported.”","start":1820.533,"stop":1825.97,"duration":5.44},{"text":"That's the argument, isn't it?","start":1825.97,"stop":1826.953,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not what the Secretary did.","start":1826.953,"stop":1828.751,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- but -- but -- what do you say to that?Could he do that?","start":1828.751,"stop":1832.001,"duration":3.25},{"text":"Could he say, \"Yes, I'm a free man.","start":1832.001,"stop":1834.679,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I'm unbounded.","start":1834.679,"stop":1835.963,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I can do what I please.","start":1835.963,"stop":1837.668,"duration":1.7},{"text":"I choose not to do what I please.","start":1837.668,"stop":1839.404,"duration":1.74},{"text":"I choose to be governed by a particular procedure,\" is he then -- will he then justify that procedure?","start":1839.404,"stop":1844.934,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1844.934,"stop":1845.459,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1845.459,"stop":1845.552,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not what he did in this case.","start":1845.552,"stop":1847.067,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1847.067,"stop":1847.662,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not what he did in this case.","start":1847.662,"stop":1848.869,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, therefore -- but that isn't the argument you made a few minutes ago.","start":1848.869,"stop":1851.811,"duration":2.94},{"text":"You -- your argument a few minutes ago, I misapprehended it.","start":1851.811,"stop":1854.663,"duration":2.85},{"text":"It was that this special provision, one can understand why, relating to the State Department authorized the Secretary of State to dispense from Service without any man's brief.","start":1854.663,"stop":1869.979,"duration":15.32}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Right so.","start":1869.979,"stop":1870.872,"duration":0.89},{"text":"Now --","start":1870.872,"stop":1870.915,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and therefore, that being so, we don't just look at this other things.","start":1870.915,"stop":1874.787,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"As long as he exercises his authority under that statute.","start":1874.787,"stop":1878.03,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1878.03,"stop":1878.575,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"And you're --","start":1878.575,"stop":1878.628,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, you have to establish that he didn't purport to act under some -- under one of the --","start":1878.628,"stop":1884.96,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1884.96,"stop":1885.113,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- defined procedures, isn't that right?","start":1885.113,"stop":1886.899,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":1886.899,"stop":1887.584,"duration":0.69},{"text":"What I have to establish and what this record makes perfectly plain is that he acted and specifically stated that he acted under two authorities, each independent.","start":1887.584,"stop":1898.904,"duration":11.32},{"text":"One was the Loyalty Order, but quite independently of that, the Secretary said, \"I exercise my discretion under the absolute discretion statute.\"","start":1898.904,"stop":1909.146,"duration":10.24},{"text":"He didn't use those words but he referred to the statute by --","start":1909.146,"stop":1910.834,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would -- it may be important in this context?","start":1910.834,"stop":1912.459,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he said --","start":1912.459,"stop":1914.227,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what they're dealing with in your own words.","start":1914.227,"stop":1915.02,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1915.02,"stop":1917.761,"duration":2.74},{"text":"What he said was, \"I understood that the responsibility was vested in me to make the determination, both under Executive Order 9835 and under Section 103 of Public Law 188,” and that section was the part of absolute discretion statute.","start":1917.761,"stop":1932.144,"duration":14.38},{"text":"And then, in the next paragraph, \"Acting in the exercise of the authority vested in me by Executive Order 9835 and also by Section 103, I made a determination to terminate it.\"","start":1932.144,"stop":1950.761,"duration":18.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. MacGuineas, may I get back with you for a moment to your comparison of the discretion under this statute with the authority in the President at his pleasure to terminate the incumbency of the Secretary of State himself?","start":1950.761,"stop":1970.206,"duration":19.44},{"text":"Now, I gather the Government's position is that in the case of the President terminating the Secretary of State.","start":1970.206,"stop":1977.839,"duration":7.63},{"text":"Now, the President may do that at his pleasure whether or not the President deems that termination necessary or advisable in the interest of the United States may.","start":1977.839,"stop":1989.625,"duration":11.79}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1989.625,"stop":1990.119,"duration":0.49},{"text":"There's no such statutory limitation on the President's discretion.","start":1990.119,"stop":1992.477,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1992.477,"stop":1993.172,"duration":0.69},{"text":"Well, now, what do you do then with the language of Section 103 which while it speaks in and -- and actually the wording is to terminate in his absolute discretion.","start":1993.172,"stop":2005.91,"duration":12.74},{"text":"That termination is tied to a standard, isn't it, whenever he shall deem such termination necessary or advisable in the interest of the United States?","start":2005.91,"stop":2013.765,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2013.765,"stop":2014.538,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the discretion is not as complete and the Secretary of State to terminate Mr. Service as would have been the discretion of the -- or the authority of the President to terminate Mr. Acheson.","start":2014.538,"stop":2025.821,"duration":11.28}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"If one could conceive of a case where the Secretary of State --","start":2025.821,"stop":2029.011,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, please.","start":2029.011,"stop":2030.037,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm sorry.","start":2030.037,"stop":2030.799,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's two, isn't it?","start":2030.799,"stop":2030.993,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's right.","start":2030.993,"stop":2031.638,"duration":0.64},{"text":"There is that qualification.","start":2031.638,"stop":2033.146,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't that --","start":2033.146,"stop":2033.881,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"The Secretary must decide in his absolute discretion that it is in the interest of the United States to dismiss petitioner.","start":2033.881,"stop":2042.358,"duration":8.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then -- then, that being so, his discretion is not as absolute as is the authority of the President to terminate him at his pleasure.","start":2042.358,"stop":2050.793,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I say it is.","start":2050.793,"stop":2051.295,"duration":0.5},{"text":"I concede it is subject to that one qualification.","start":2051.295,"stop":2054.023,"duration":2.73},{"text":"So, the only question --","start":2054.023,"stop":2054.065,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's an important qualification, isn't it?","start":2054.065,"stop":2056.193,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But the only question then in this case is did the Secretary make that determination?","start":2056.193,"stop":2062.054,"duration":5.86},{"text":"We think in his affidavit plainly establishes that he did make the determination to exercise his authority under the absolute discretion statute.","start":2062.054,"stop":2072.101,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That isn't what he said, Mr. MacGuineas.","start":2072.101,"stop":2074.652,"duration":2.55},{"text":"If you will read and I still insist but not only if I have before me an affidavit of the Secretary of State but one who -- one doesn't have to take much judicial notice, a singularly careful and acute lawyer, to use his language with care.","start":2074.652,"stop":2091.777,"duration":17.13},{"text":"In paragraph 4, he said, “Acting in the exercise, I made a determination to determining -- I made a determination to terminate.\"","start":2091.777,"stop":2103.7,"duration":11.92},{"text":"That's his conclusion.","start":2103.7,"stop":2105.799,"duration":2.1},{"text":"The next paragraph tells you the basis of his conclusion and the basis of his conclusion, \"I made that determination solely, solely as the result of the findings of Loyalty Review Board and as a result of my review in the opinion of that Court.\"","start":2105.799,"stop":2124.238,"duration":18.44},{"text":"So, namely, that having decided, he had his legislative authority.","start":2124.238,"stop":2130.169,"duration":5.93},{"text":"He had the general security system, loyalty scheme.","start":2130.169,"stop":2137.308,"duration":7.14},{"text":"One must take oneself back to January 1953.","start":2137.308,"stop":2141.529,"duration":4.22},{"text":"That is a very dominant consideration in the mind of everybody from the president, down.","start":2141.529,"stop":2147.753,"duration":6.22},{"text":"I made a determination in the light of the -- having -- having the authority of Loyalty Program gave me and the McCarran Act.","start":2147.753,"stop":2158.63,"duration":10.88},{"text":"I made a determination of severance, but it stopped there.","start":2158.63,"stop":2162.996,"duration":4.37},{"text":"I think we would have one argument, but he goes on and says, \"I made that determination, solely as a result of the finding of the Loyalty Review Board.\"","start":2162.996,"stop":2174.382,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what the Secretary of State seems to me plain enough to be saying there is this, \"I exercise my statutory discretion.","start":2174.382,"stop":2181.619,"duration":7.24},{"text":"The only datum, the only fact which I had before me which caused me to exercise that discretion was the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board.\"","start":2181.619,"stop":2193.012,"duration":11.39},{"text":"In other words, he said, \"The only thing I looked at when I made up my mind was to read the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board.\"","start":2193.012,"stop":2201.244,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Now, that brings us to the heart of the petitioner's case.","start":2201.244,"stop":2204.645,"duration":3.4},{"text":"Concededly, the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board in it and of itself was not an act of Government.","start":2204.645,"stop":2212.411,"duration":7.77},{"text":"It did not establish any legal rights or obligations, either the petitioner or the Government.","start":2212.411,"stop":2218.84,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he know that then?","start":2218.84,"stop":2220.247,"duration":1.41},{"text":"Did the Secretary of State know that then or was that later decided?","start":2220.247,"stop":2226.466,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That was decided by this Court after the Secretary acted.","start":2226.466,"stop":2230.381,"duration":3.91},{"text":"When the --","start":2230.381,"stop":2230.444,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time the Secretary acted on it, it was -- I suppose to be was it not, a legal finding by Board with power to do so.","start":2230.444,"stop":2239.527,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2239.527,"stop":2239.871,"duration":0.34},{"text":"Now, what the Secretary himself actually knew about that situation, as Mr. Justice Frankfurter pointed out, this was a Secretary who is an exceptionally acute liar.","start":2239.871,"stop":2251.431,"duration":11.56},{"text":"What he actually knew about that situation is not disclosed by the record.","start":2251.431,"stop":2257.069,"duration":5.64},{"text":"Our contention in that is --","start":2257.069,"stop":2258.443,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose he could know how the Court would have decided it, he have decided two years later, did he?","start":2258.443,"stop":2264.19,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I think there are some lawyers who consider they can prognosticate this Court's opinions.","start":2264.19,"stop":2270.641,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did -- did you find anything in what he said about that order that indicates even prognosticating --","start":2270.641,"stop":2275.609,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I say --","start":2275.609,"stop":2275.953,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that it was a bad order?","start":2275.953,"stop":2277.237,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I say the record is -- the record is blank on that subject.","start":2277.237,"stop":2280.69,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's fair to the Department to say the Department didn't prognosticate that.","start":2280.69,"stop":2284.943,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"As quite fair -- quite fair.","start":2284.943,"stop":2289.429,"duration":4.49},{"text":"But then, the point comes down to this.","start":2289.429,"stop":2291.508,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I take the precious sole, Mr. MacGuineas, but why -- why isn't what the Secretary said reasonably we understood the saying in effect.","start":2291.508,"stop":2304.515,"duration":13.01},{"text":"Well if that Board thinks that it's not in the interest of the United States to continue Mr. Service in employment from the State Department, I ought not asks for any other assurance that perhaps he maybe safely retained.","start":2304.515,"stop":2327.724,"duration":23.21},{"text":"But I'll follow the Loyalty Board and exercise my discretion since that's the way they feel about it determining.","start":2327.724,"stop":2337.461,"duration":9.74},{"text":"Why can't that affidavit be reasonably be read as in effect saying that?","start":2337.461,"stop":2341.867,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it may or it may also be what the Secretary of State may have had in mind was this.","start":2341.867,"stop":2348.759,"duration":6.89},{"text":"He may have said well, the Board has made this decision of the doubtful loyalty.","start":2348.759,"stop":2354.667,"duration":5.91},{"text":"He said, I don't -- I don't agree with the Board.","start":2354.667,"stop":2357.085,"duration":2.42},{"text":"But nevertheless, that is a decision of a Board which goes to the press.","start":2357.085,"stop":2361.963,"duration":4.88},{"text":"It affects the relations of the Department of State with Congress and with the public and I deem within the interest of the United States in the light of that fair fact that the -- such an opinion has been issued that Mr. Service be dispensed.","start":2361.963,"stop":2376.578,"duration":14.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, if he had known that, what developed only two years later or whatever the time was much later, that in fact that conclusion was not well-founded by the Board in light of the erroneous reliance upon some of the material which the Board used to reach its conclusion.","start":2376.578,"stop":2398.445,"duration":21.87},{"text":"Isn't it also a -- a safe inference that he would not have taken the action he did simply on the Board's?","start":2398.445,"stop":2404.543,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think so at all because as I say, he -- he might have said, I think this opinion is completely wrong as far as what it says about Mr. Service's doubtful loyalty.","start":2404.543,"stop":2416.781,"duration":12.24},{"text":"But nevertheless, it is one of the facts of light that this opinion has been issued --","start":2416.781,"stop":2421.658,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suggest --","start":2421.658,"stop":2421.932,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and the law --","start":2421.932,"stop":2422.587,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that if he had said in this affidavit, I think, that the Board is dead wrong for the reasons which subsequently the Court said the Board was dead wrong.","start":2422.587,"stop":2432.561,"duration":9.97},{"text":"It's unreasonable inference to suggest and say, I, therefore, have nothing before me, which indicates that he should be terminated and I won't terminate.","start":2432.561,"stop":2441.267,"duration":8.71}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I suggest that assumes that the Secretary of State in making this kind of an absolute discretion determination has to act upon something that has legal significance or legal effect.","start":2441.267,"stop":2453.165,"duration":11.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But he thought he did evidently because -- then I come to the other point, I -- I -- unless I have to.","start":2453.165,"stop":2459.617,"duration":6.45},{"text":"I wouldn't attribute redundancy to any statement by Mr. -- by Mr. Acheson.","start":2459.617,"stop":2464.793,"duration":5.18},{"text":"I wouldn't attribute to him making half a page to write a lot of stuff that -- that is wholly irrelevant.","start":2464.793,"stop":2472.941,"duration":8.15},{"text":"Then, this -- which brings me to a question on which I would like your candid, at least that you're not candid, but you ought to have no -- you're unhesitant reply.","start":2472.941,"stop":2482.557,"duration":9.62},{"text":"As I listen to your argument, say, for the last two minutes, it goes through to my mind a thought -- I think I would like to have your opinion, perhaps tomorrow, but the question of relevance.","start":2482.557,"stop":2499.585,"duration":17.03},{"text":"Am I entitled to take into account in reading this paragraph?","start":2499.585,"stop":2503.69,"duration":4.11},{"text":"Am I entitled to find light on this paragraph from the fact that Mr. Acheson since fully unrelated to this case has written a book in which he deals with the problem with the Loyalty Program.","start":2503.69,"stop":2519.274,"duration":15.58},{"text":"And looking back, he finds that he, himself, now regrets his share in carrying out that program or his share in supporting that program.","start":2519.274,"stop":2530.058,"duration":10.78},{"text":"If you will tell me, I must put that out of my mind.","start":2530.058,"stop":2532.428,"duration":2.37},{"text":"I can assure you why it's humanly possible, I shall.","start":2532.428,"stop":2536.571,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And I wish you'd be very unhesitant to tell me whether you think that that's the kind of thing that one is puzzled about this thing has the right to take into account as indicating as -- as the light in which this is to be read, as you know what I'm referring to --","start":2536.571,"stop":2551.693,"duration":15.12}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2551.693,"stop":2551.776,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that is about last year.","start":2551.776,"stop":2553.421,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Quite candidly, I'll state to Your Honor that whatever Mr. Acheson's present views maybe about the Loyalty Program or his part --","start":2553.421,"stop":2563.472,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not this case.","start":2563.472,"stop":2563.906,"duration":0.43},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2563.906,"stop":2564.348,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, the whole program and his participation in it has nothing whatever to do with this case.","start":2564.348,"stop":2569.557,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that --","start":2569.557,"stop":2570.372,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But because --","start":2570.372,"stop":2570.453,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but you must dismiss it --","start":2570.453,"stop":2571.613,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2571.613,"stop":2571.636,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as to getting light, all right.","start":2571.636,"stop":2572.95,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it's quite irrelevant because he may say in effect, \"I'm sorry I did it,\" but that's not saying that he didn't have the authority to do it --","start":2572.95,"stop":2580.829,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but --","start":2580.829,"stop":2580.842,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and that what he did was not legal.","start":2580.842,"stop":2582.708,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to argue because I think you would switch, but -- but I just want to know why that doesn't shed light as to the significance in his decision of a program and the compulsions of a program which he then felt compelled to respect and indeed to promote which he now regard as bad as shown that -- that that did have a hold on him.","start":2582.708,"stop":2606.826,"duration":24.12}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our point is and as far as the judging the validity of the exercise of this discretion, it doesn't make a slightest difference whether the datum on which he relied was an opinion by a Board, whether it was a newspaper editorial, whether it was a letter from the Congressman, whether it was a causal conversation from a friend.","start":2606.826,"stop":2628.434,"duration":21.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you.","start":2628.434,"stop":2628.989,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2628.989,"stop":2629.544,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's the way he disclosed his mind, but if he disclosed his mind on a ground which is not something that he had a right to take in or rather if -- if he discloses his mind of how he acted on that, therefore, having operated within the framework of the administrative procedure called the Loyalty Program, then, I hope before you sit down, you indicate how that differs from the Elg case?","start":2629.544,"stop":2655.46,"duration":25.92}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I must take to Your Honor's statement that he made a decision on something they didn't have a right to take in.","start":2655.46,"stop":2660.866,"duration":5.41},{"text":"That's just my point.","start":2660.866,"stop":2662.715,"duration":1.85},{"text":"He did have the right to look at this opinion whether it was legal or illegal.","start":2662.715,"stop":2668.084,"duration":5.37},{"text":"He had the right for instance.","start":2668.084,"stop":2669.378,"duration":1.29},{"text":"Suppose he had said, \"I make this decision solely on the basis of the court case in Jones versus Smith.”","start":2669.378,"stop":2676.362,"duration":6.98},{"text":"And subsequently, it turns out that the decision in Jones versus Smith was rendered by a court without jurisdiction.","start":2676.362,"stop":2682.483,"duration":6.12},{"text":"Would that vitiate the Secretary's exercise of absolute discretion?","start":2682.483,"stop":2686.246,"duration":3.76},{"text":"I say no.","start":2686.246,"stop":2687.984,"duration":1.74},{"text":"\"Absolute discretion\" means jurisdiction to decide rightly or wrongly.","start":2687.984,"stop":2693.872,"duration":5.89},{"text":"It means jurisdiction to decide without subject to review by any other organ of Government and that is plainly what Congress meant, would emphatically used the word \"absolute discretion.\"","start":2693.872,"stop":2706.805,"duration":12.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time that Secretary Hall denied that passport to that Swedish lady, she was Swedish, Danish, whatever.","start":2706.805,"stop":2719.211,"duration":12.41},{"text":"Sorry, going on, Mr. Elg.","start":2719.211,"stop":2721.348,"duration":2.14},{"text":"At the time that Secretary Hall withheld a passport from her, he could have withheld the passport at that time.","start":2721.348,"stop":2729.021,"duration":7.67},{"text":"I think the law seems to be clear that the Secretary of State had untrammeled discretion in the matter.","start":2729.021,"stop":2735.711,"duration":6.69},{"text":"I don't mean to imply controversy and I simply state what the opinion, what the law then was.","start":2735.711,"stop":2741.351,"duration":5.64},{"text":"But that isn't what Secretary Hall did.","start":2741.351,"stop":2743.197,"duration":1.85},{"text":"He gave a reason and there was argued at the bar of this Court, I think as vigorously and as confident as your argue is.","start":2743.197,"stop":2752.719,"duration":9.52},{"text":"It's is one of my first arguments, I remember, that first arguments that I heard.","start":2752.719,"stop":2757.667,"duration":4.95},{"text":"That in as much as the Secretary had absolute power for good reason, bad reason, no reason at all.","start":2757.667,"stop":2768.057,"duration":10.39},{"text":"The fact that he gave a reason that isn't any good doesn't limit his power.","start":2768.057,"stop":2772.019,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But the point is --","start":2772.019,"stop":2772.283,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And this pointed out the opposite.","start":2772.283,"stop":2773.64,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2773.64,"stop":2774.643,"duration":1},{"text":"Now, the distinction between this situation and the Perkins v.Elg situation is this, as I see it.","start":2774.643,"stop":2781.987,"duration":7.34},{"text":"The passport statute does not give the Secretary of State absolute discretion.","start":2781.987,"stop":2787.276,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It did at that time.","start":2787.276,"stop":2789.596,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2789.596,"stop":2790.783,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2790.783,"stop":2791.498,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- the Government may have so argued --","start":2791.498,"stop":2793.895,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2793.895,"stop":2794.347,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but if so, the Government was mistaken.","start":2794.347,"stop":2795.965,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It came if you let me --","start":2795.965,"stop":2796.79,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":2796.79,"stop":2796.931,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- say so as one who had something to do with it years ago.","start":2796.931,"stop":2799.943,"duration":3.01},{"text":"It came to me as a great shock to find that they could be any question about it.","start":2799.943,"stop":2803.895,"duration":3.95},{"text":"And that's why I'm saying the assumption of Perkins against Elg is that the Secretary has absolute power, except, he gave a reason and this Court said, “That reason is no good.”","start":2803.895,"stop":2815.246,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what this Court conclusively established as an interpretation of the passport statute in Perkins v.Elg is that the Secretary of State's discretion is not untrammeled, that it is subject to judicial review with respect to issues of law.","start":2815.246,"stop":2833.604,"duration":18.36},{"text":"Now, here -- and then, may I say otherwise, you are not dealing there with problems so internal to the executive branch of the Government as the tenure of executive personnel.","start":2833.604,"stop":2847.578,"duration":13.97},{"text":"You were dealing with the rights of private citizens who have no employment relationship with the Government.","start":2847.578,"stop":2854.873,"duration":7.3},{"text":"And that right as established by this Court in Perkins v.Elg has about it elements of justiciability which the right or privilege of executive's tenure does not have.","start":2854.873,"stop":2869.211,"duration":14.34},{"text":"Now, even in the case of a dismissal under the Civil Service law where the phrase is, “in order to promote the efficiency of the service,” this Court has consistently held that the discretion on the executive as to the reason for dismissing the man, also the evidence or the data on which he does it is a matter of unreviewable executive discretion.","start":2869.211,"stop":2898.105,"duration":28.89},{"text":"This Court will review for compliance with prescribed procedure and that only.","start":2898.105,"stop":2905.009,"duration":6.9},{"text":"The most striking case to illustrate that is the ever lying case in 257 U.S., where a man was dismissed form the Civil Service for taking bribes.","start":2905.009,"stop":2915.637,"duration":10.63},{"text":"Subsequently, a reinvestigation was held and the President himself decided that those charges were wholly unfounded.","start":2915.637,"stop":2923.302,"duration":7.66},{"text":"The man was innocent and he was reinstated.","start":2923.302,"stop":2927.685,"duration":4.38},{"text":"He then sued in the Court of Claims for his back pay during the period that he was out of a job and the claim that came here on appeal of this Court.","start":2927.685,"stop":2936.083,"duration":8.4},{"text":"The question was whether this Court could take into account the admitted error in the initial or executive determination that the man was not guilty of the things for which he was dismissed, and this Court said, \"No.","start":2936.083,"stop":2953.09,"duration":17.01},{"text":"We can't consider that.","start":2953.09,"stop":2954.858,"duration":1.77},{"text":"That is wholly within the discretion of the executive.\"","start":2954.858,"stop":2959.231,"duration":4.37},{"text":"He got the procedure, which the law gave him to it and as far as the Courts are concerned, that's the end of the matter.","start":2959.231,"stop":2965.429,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying, if I understand it is insofar as the exercise of the 103 power is concerned, it's immaterial whether that Peters against Hobby is immaterial, that's your point, isn't it?","start":2965.429,"stop":2981.6,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because --","start":2981.6,"stop":2983.268,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, if Peters against Hobby had come down the day before Acheson exercised his 103 power, you would say that notwithstanding Peters against Hobby, he had a right to take into account that de facto action, if he choose to call it of the Loyalty Review Board which the Court held is without jurisdiction to act and could make that a basis of his 103 power discharge, is that it?","start":2983.268,"stop":3012.795,"duration":29.53}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3012.795,"stop":3013.848,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now that the Peters against Hobby comes into this only to the extent that it vitiates the discharge under the Executive Order.","start":3013.848,"stop":3023.283,"duration":9.43}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":3023.283,"stop":3023.945,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that your position?","start":3023.945,"stop":3024.587,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":3024.587,"stop":3030.026,"duration":5.44},{"text":"Now, that presents our position with respect to the --","start":3030.026,"stop":3035.354,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it said -- is it quite that?","start":3035.354,"stop":3038.878,"duration":3.52},{"text":"May I offer you another string to your bow?","start":3038.878,"stop":3042.542,"duration":3.66},{"text":"It isn't -- it isn't merely that if he acted under the Loyalty Program, then he acted under a determination, which this Court held the Board was powerless to make.","start":3042.542,"stop":3057.722,"duration":15.18},{"text":"But at least not to the string to the bow for you to pass, but the -- the difficulty here is not nearly that he doesn't -- he does the Hobby as he notified the legality of that.","start":3057.722,"stop":3072.555,"duration":14.83},{"text":"But the conditions under which the Loyalty Board as I understood Mr. Rhetts' argument that the circumstances of the -- before the Loyalty Board on the basis of which they rendered their decision to it and not now needless to say committing myself to it that they acted on testimony which was the demonstrably or concededly inaccurate, unreliable, etcetera, etcetera, made a basis for judgment which on the face of it shows couldn't have been, if it relies on -- if he parted to that into account that that is also subject to -- to challenge on the general theory that any abuse of discretion no matter how unlimited this subject to challenge.","start":3072.555,"stop":3125.966,"duration":53.41},{"text":"And that if -- that if the Secretary of State sets forth, I acted on the testimony of absolutely disreputable people.","start":3125.966,"stop":3134.619,"duration":8.65},{"text":"I'm hoping to say that this was -- I acted on the testimony of actually disreputable people, people on whose testimony I wouldn't dream of facing the slightest reliance on my own affairs of light and that's good enough for me.","start":3134.619,"stop":3147.759,"duration":13.14},{"text":"I'm not so sure you would be standing here and say, \"That's an unreviewable discretion.\"","start":3147.759,"stop":3152.677,"duration":4.92},{"text":"All discretion is subject to the implications of a Due Process Clause even though it may not be a due process problem.","start":3152.677,"stop":3160.331,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But in this field of executive employment, I do stand here and say exactly that, and I say it because it's what this Court has held time and time again.","start":3160.331,"stop":3170.126,"duration":9.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's never -- have those been cases in which the exercise of discretion was challenged as based on conduct which if it took place in the criminal case, one would say violated due process?","start":3170.126,"stop":3187.979,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly, traditional concepts of due process have never been considered applicable to executive dismissal.","start":3187.979,"stop":3196.636,"duration":8.66},{"text":"Under the Civil Service law, the employee doesn't even get any --","start":3196.636,"stop":3199.204,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when you say they've never been considered?","start":3199.204,"stop":3202.233,"duration":3.03},{"text":"They may -- certainly, Perkins v.Elg was a brand new decision so far as anybody who is earning a knowledge of the law was concerned.","start":3202.233,"stop":3209.093,"duration":6.86},{"text":"When you say it's never been considered, one can say it's never been before this Court that the basis of determination was something which if conceded by the Government would in a criminal case involve violation of due process.","start":3209.093,"stop":3222.309,"duration":13.22}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all I'm pointing out is that in the Civil Service dismissal, the employee doesn't even get a hearing in the most rudimentary sense of the term.","start":3222.309,"stop":3229.792,"duration":7.48},{"text":"And yet, no one has ever contend that -- that there is any due process question involved in that, the employee --","start":3229.792,"stop":3235.372,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you entirely.","start":3235.372,"stop":3236.96,"duration":1.59},{"text":"I -- I for myself go with you most of the way, almost all the way that under 30 -- under 103, the Secretary of State in just -- had this Secretary tell Mr. Jones that his services will terminate that afternoon and he is not responsible to anybody.","start":3236.96,"stop":3256.203,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming --","start":3256.203,"stop":3256.504,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A different question is raised if he gives the reason.","start":3256.504,"stop":3260.576,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3260.576,"stop":3261.76,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And if that reason is an invalid reason.","start":3261.76,"stop":3264.862,"duration":3.1},{"text":"But, are we getting attention to the whole of the affidavit of the Secretary?","start":3264.862,"stop":3269.757,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Do we end the discussions thus far take account of the last paragraph of it or any sense in determining to terminate the service of Mr. Service?","start":3269.757,"stop":3279.015,"duration":9.26},{"text":"I did not consider that I was legally bound or required by the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board to take such action.","start":3279.015,"stop":3286.079,"duration":7.06},{"text":"On the contrary, I consider that the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board was merely an advisory recommendation to me.","start":3286.079,"stop":3295.202,"duration":9.12},{"text":"And that I was legally free to exercise my own judgment as to whether Mr. Service's employment should be terminated and I did solely exercise that judgment.","start":3295.202,"stop":3306.049,"duration":10.85},{"text":"Is that what he said?","start":3306.049,"stop":3306.744,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3306.744,"stop":3307.857,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Now, what the Secretary is saying there is, \"I recognize that this opinion of the Loyalty Review Board had no more force than a newspaper article.","start":3307.857,"stop":3319.434,"duration":11.58},{"text":"I was free to accept it or reject it.","start":3319.434,"stop":3322.446,"duration":3.01},{"text":"I chose to look at that and --","start":3322.446,"stop":3326.859,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you please tell me why you used the word legally free?","start":3326.859,"stop":3331.927,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"What he meant was that he --","start":3331.927,"stop":3334.167,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Legally free of it.","start":3334.167,"stop":3335.574,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"What he meant was that he was not --","start":3335.574,"stop":3336.607,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was in the light of -- or the whole paragraph.","start":3336.607,"stop":3338.844,"duration":2.24},{"text":"I quite agree with my Brother Whittaker.","start":3338.844,"stop":3340.79,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"What he meant was that he was not taken in by the general memorandum which the Loyalty Review Board had issued to all agencies in which they said, “The head of the agencies must carry out our mandate.”","start":3340.79,"stop":3354.355,"duration":13.57},{"text":"And he, as you say, wasn't a student of -- a lawyer to appreciate that that was not the law.","start":3354.355,"stop":3358.382,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you -- could you take the two minutes that's remaining to deal what seems to me to be the real trouble in this case.","start":3358.382,"stop":3364.894,"duration":6.51},{"text":"And that is, how can you justify the departure from the regulations assuming that the regulations were applicable to the 103 -- the 103 power?","start":3364.894,"stop":3382.656,"duration":17.76}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, our position, which I can only state in summary fashion on the regulations argument, is this.","start":3382.656,"stop":3387.945,"duration":5.29},{"text":"First, those regulations by their own terms are dealing with terminations on these grounds either of loyalty or security.","start":3387.945,"stop":3399.426,"duration":11.48},{"text":"This was not a termination of petitioner, either for loyalty or security ground.","start":3399.426,"stop":3404.793,"duration":5.37},{"text":"This was a pure termination in the interest of the United States.","start":3404.793,"stop":3408.327,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the --","start":3408.327,"stop":3408.581,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where do you -- where do you get that?","start":3408.581,"stop":3410.911,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that's the language of the statute.","start":3410.911,"stop":3412.94,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What if -- is that said in the --","start":3412.94,"stop":3414.485,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's --","start":3414.485,"stop":3415.341,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- termination notice to him that was given on December 30?","start":3415.341,"stop":3418.293,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"What is said in the notice is that the Secretary exercised his authority under the statute citing it which says, \"Terminate in the interest of the United States.\"","start":3418.293,"stop":3427.89,"duration":9.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And he said he acted solely on the basis of the Loyalty Report.","start":3427.89,"stop":3432.354,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but that doesn't mean that he --","start":3432.354,"stop":3433.892,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did that Loyalty Board have a -- have jurisdiction over everything besides loyalty?","start":3433.892,"stop":3439.121,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":3439.121,"stop":3440.147,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- but did it have --","start":3440.147,"stop":3440.491,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"That doesn't mean --","start":3440.491,"stop":3441.093,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- jurisdiction over except to cases relating to security and loyalty?","start":3441.093,"stop":3444.717,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"It had none -- none but --","start":3444.717,"stop":3446.044,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And did he say or not that he acted solely on the basis of their finding?","start":3446.044,"stop":3450.54,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but that didn't mean to say that he accepted their conclusion that he was loyal.","start":3450.54,"stop":3453.882,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether he did or not if -- if that's the sole thing they acted on and all they had to do with was security and loyalty.","start":3453.882,"stop":3461.684,"duration":7.8},{"text":"How can you say that this man was discharged for anything except something to do with security and loyalty?","start":3461.684,"stop":3469.147,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because he was discharged under the statute, and the statute under which --","start":3469.147,"stop":3473.072,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of what was said into the Loyalty Report.","start":3473.072,"stop":3475.984,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"But not that the Secretary concluded that this man was disloyal merely because he read an opinion.","start":3475.984,"stop":3482.868,"duration":6.88},{"text":"He may have disagreed with everything in that opinion and still said --","start":3482.868,"stop":3485.78,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And still said, “I'm doing it solely on the ground of what they said.”","start":3485.78,"stop":3489.464,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"He said, “No.”","start":3489.464,"stop":3490.229,"duration":0.76},{"text":"You can say that he said, “Yes.”","start":3490.229,"stop":3491.443,"duration":1.21},{"text":"The only thing I looked at was this opinion.","start":3491.443,"stop":3495.027,"duration":3.58},{"text":"Now, the second point on the regulation is that even if you are --","start":3495.027,"stop":3498.069,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't seem to me you've answered that because --","start":3498.069,"stop":3500.948,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3500.948,"stop":3501.573,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what he said in his affidavit in effect is that had it not been -- put it in another way, had it not been for the Loyalty Review Report, the Board's Report, this fellow wouldn't have been discharged.","start":3501.573,"stop":3513.162,"duration":11.59}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"No, doubt about that but --","start":3513.162,"stop":3514.075,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's the difference between that in substance, the real substance of discharging him for loyalty reasons?","start":3514.075,"stop":3519.825,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference is what I thought I had previously indicated.","start":3519.825,"stop":3522.908,"duration":3.08},{"text":"The Secretary may have looked at this report and he said, \"I don't believe a word in this report, but it's the only thing I'm going to look at.","start":3522.908,"stop":3530.504,"duration":7.6},{"text":"But nevertheless, the pubic relations at the time indicate that it's desirable to dismiss the Secretary.\"","start":3530.504,"stop":3537.317,"duration":6.81},{"text":"Now, that's not a dismissal on loyalty grounds, to security grounds.","start":3537.317,"stop":3540.973,"duration":3.66},{"text":"It's merely a dismissal because the Secretary conceded to be in the interest of the United States under all the circumstances to dismiss the man.","start":3540.973,"stop":3547.736,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that what they told Service, they discharged him for?","start":3547.736,"stop":3551.353,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was -- the Secretary told him.","start":3551.353,"stop":3553.63,"duration":2.28},{"text":"He said, \"I am discharging you, both under the loyalty ground and under the absolute discretion statute.\"","start":3553.63,"stop":3562.322,"duration":8.69},{"text":"Now, the second point, if I may proceed on the regulation point is that even if contrary to our contention, the Court treats those regulations as applicable to an exercise of absolute discretion in the interest of the United States.","start":3562.322,"stop":3579.622,"duration":17.3},{"text":"Those regulations were complied with.","start":3579.622,"stop":3582.574,"duration":2.95},{"text":"I --I regret that the time does not permit but the details of that are set forth in our brief.","start":3582.574,"stop":3588.936,"duration":6.36},{"text":"The final and last point is the one which was not raised by the Government's result, was advanced only by the Courts and the suggestion that Congress passing this statute in the circumstances that existed at the time, was all these procedural laws in effect intended that this discretion be exercised without any procedure, whatever.","start":3588.936,"stop":3616.586,"duration":27.65},{"text":"And that therefore, if the Secretary under that statute turns right around and proscribed the same procedure that he had already he's merely nullifying the course of the statute.","start":3616.586,"stop":3625.418,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You said that the Government didn't raise that point.","start":3625.418,"stop":3628.337,"duration":2.92},{"text":"Do you support -- do you undertake to support that reasoning?","start":3628.337,"stop":3630.815,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- we -- yes.","start":3630.815,"stop":3631.52,"duration":0.7},{"text":"We -- we state that as a -- a ground because it was stated by the courts below.","start":3631.52,"stop":3637.378,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"By the Court of Appeals.","start":3637.378,"stop":3638.916,"duration":1.54},{"text":"You don't make any independent argument in support of it?","start":3638.916,"stop":3642.58,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- no.","start":3642.58,"stop":3643.385,"duration":0.81},{"text":"We have no grounds except as stated by the Court.","start":3643.385,"stop":3645.351,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is -- is that -- is that what Mr. Rhetts was referring to when he said as an argument that the regulations are invalid --","start":3645.351,"stop":3652.474,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3652.474,"stop":3652.484,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- ultra vires?","start":3652.484,"stop":3653.307,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3653.307,"stop":3653.316,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your point, namely, that this would be undercutting what Congress has provided.","start":3653.316,"stop":3657.398,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. MacGuineas","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3657.398,"stop":3662.985,"duration":5.59}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 02, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13229","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 407, John S.Service, Petitioner versus John Foster Dulles et al.","start":0,"stop":11.431,"duration":11.43},{"text":"Mr. Rhetts.","start":11.431,"stop":12.671,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":12.671,"stop":14.821,"duration":2.15},{"text":"This case is here on a writ of certiorari, directed to the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit to review that Court's affirmance of the District Court judgment, which denied petitioner's motion for summary judgment and granted respondent's cross-motion.","start":14.821,"stop":37.173,"duration":22.35},{"text":"The question in the case is as to the legality of petitioner's dismissal from the Foreign Service of the United States by the Secretary of State on December 14, 1951.","start":37.173,"stop":54.445,"duration":17.27},{"text":"From 1935 until December 1951, petitioner served continuously in China as a Foreign Service Officer of the United States.","start":54.445,"stop":69.375,"duration":14.93},{"text":"In 1943, he was detached from the Foreign Service at the request of Secretary of War Stimson, and for two years, served as a political advisor to General Stilwell, and when that officer was relieved from command of the China-Burma Theater to General Wedemeyer.","start":69.375,"stop":94.77,"duration":25.39},{"text":"In addition to general political reporting, petitioner's duties when attached to the military involved the maintenance of a very close relationships with American Press representatives who visited the China Theater of War.","start":94.77,"stop":113.384,"duration":18.61},{"text":"And in accordance to the General Stilwell's policies, freely briefing such press representatives on the political situation in China which provided the background for the military operations in that theater.","start":113.384,"stop":132.239,"duration":18.86},{"text":"In April 1945, petitioner was recalled to the United States.","start":132.239,"stop":138.989,"duration":6.75},{"text":"And before leaving, he sought and obtained permission from the military authority under which he functioned to retain and to bring with him copies of various -- personal copies of various memoranda and reports, which he had prepared while on duty assigned to General Stilwell and General Wedemeyer.","start":138.989,"stop":167.68,"duration":28.69},{"text":"He arrived in Washington on April 12, 1945.","start":167.68,"stop":173.772,"duration":6.09},{"text":"Now, on March 10th, 1945, more than a month before he returned to this country, the Office of Strategic Services made a raid on the offices of one Philip Jaffe, the editor of the magazine called Amerasia in New York City.","start":173.772,"stop":193.622,"duration":19.85},{"text":"On this occasion, the raiding officers discovered a large number of government documents originating in the files of the O.S.S., the State-War-Navy, and other departments of the Government.","start":193.622,"stop":209.055,"duration":15.43},{"text":"The case was immediately turned over to the FBI which after an investigation on April 18th, 1945, proposed to present the case to the Department of Justice for prosecution against the magazine editor Jaffe, a State Department employee, not the petitioner, a naval officer and others.","start":209.055,"stop":236.805,"duration":27.75},{"text":"However, the case was not been turned over for prosecution because the State and Navy Departments requested that the FBI's investigation be continued for an additional period.","start":236.805,"stop":248.665,"duration":11.86},{"text":"On the next day, April 19th, 1945, petitioner was introduced to Jaffe by an American naval officer on duty in the Far Eastern branch of the Office of Naval Intelligence here in Washington, who quite unknown to petitioner was one of those implicated in the wholesale of government document thievery which the O.S.S.and the FBI had uncovered.","start":248.665,"stop":289.239,"duration":40.57},{"text":"And so, it came about that when petitioner was introduced to what he supposed to be a reputable journalist, the editor of a specialist magazine on Far Eastern Affairs by what he supposed to be a reputable naval officer on duty in the Office of -- Office of Naval Intelligence.","start":289.239,"stop":313.722,"duration":24.48},{"text":"He was in fact being introduced to a man on whom the FBI's net had already closed and who was quite literally wired for sound.","start":313.722,"stop":332.738,"duration":19.02},{"text":"Believing Jaffe to be a journalist of repute, the petitioner talked with Jaffe in his hotel room, in Jaffe's hotel room in the City of Washington on four different occasions between April 19th and May 29th, 1945.","start":332.738,"stop":354.364,"duration":21.63},{"text":"And he very ill-advisedly lent to Jaffe some copies of his memoranda, which I have referred to before, which he brought back with him from China.","start":354.364,"stop":369.296,"duration":14.93},{"text":"These memoranda were characterized later by the Loyalty Review Board of the Civil Service Commission as being, and I quote them, \"For the most part, such as a newspaper reporter on the spot would prepare for his newspaper.\"","start":369.296,"stop":385.639,"duration":16.34},{"text":"And as to some of these, the Loyalty Review Board said they might be considered as hot news.Petitioner's conversations with Jaffe were secretly recorded by the FBI by the use of a microphone which was planted in Jaffe's hotel room.","start":385.639,"stop":405.157,"duration":19.52},{"text":"On June 6th, 1945, petitioner along with Jaffe, the naval officer who had introduced him to Jaffe, another State Department employee and several others were arrested.","start":405.157,"stop":419.727,"duration":14.57},{"text":"And after volunteering his testimony, petitioner was the subject of a unanimous no true bill returned by the grand jury in his case.","start":419.727,"stop":433.427,"duration":13.7},{"text":"He was thereafter duly restored to duty after hearing before the Board of Foreign Service personnel.","start":433.427,"stop":442.627,"duration":9.2},{"text":"Now, five years later, in 1950, petitioner along with the then Secretary of State Acheson and others was the subject of a personal attack on the floor of the United States Senate.","start":442.627,"stop":460.352,"duration":17.72},{"text":"And shortly thereafter, the Loyalty Review Board of the Civil Service Commission directed the State Department's Loyalty Security Board to reopen its previous favorable findings as to petitioner's loyalty and as to whether or not he was a security risk.","start":460.352,"stop":484.478,"duration":24.13},{"text":"And directed the State Department Board to prefer charges against --","start":484.478,"stop":489.833,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I missed that, Mr. Rhetts.","start":489.833,"stop":490.513,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- petitioner.","start":490.513,"stop":493.573,"duration":3.06},{"text":"The --","start":493.573,"stop":493.633,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a -- there was a no true bill by the grand jury.","start":493.633,"stop":496.863,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":496.863,"stop":497.726,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- up to that moment, was he still in the Department?","start":497.726,"stop":501.016,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":501.016,"stop":502.026,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And when did he -- when was he detached from or -- or, and when was there an investigation by the State Department's Loyalty Board after this no true bill?","start":502.026,"stop":514.226,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The no true bill was 1945.","start":514.226,"stop":516.645,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":516.645,"stop":518.296,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"He was the subject of investigation at various times.","start":518.296,"stop":521.035,"duration":2.74},{"text":"The President's Loyalty Order did not come along until 1947.","start":521.035,"stop":525.736,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Thereafter, in accordance with the direction of that Court --","start":525.736,"stop":527.596,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Continued from 1945 to 1947 as a --","start":527.596,"stop":530.406,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"In new --","start":530.406,"stop":530.476,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- State Department officer.","start":530.476,"stop":531.566,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"In new posts, received promotions and so on.","start":531.566,"stop":534.85,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, go from -- go on from there, before you get to the restoration of the inquiry.","start":534.85,"stop":539.04,"duration":4.19},{"text":"What -- when -- when was there the first, the security scheme came into -- in 1947, is it not?","start":539.04,"stop":546.88,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"1947.","start":546.88,"stop":547.96,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, was he then subjected at once to a Loyalty investigation?","start":547.96,"stop":551.45,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"He was.","start":551.45,"stop":552.67,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the State Department?","start":552.67,"stop":553.518,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"In the State Department.","start":553.518,"stop":554.098,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"By the Department's Loyalty Board?","start":554.098,"stop":556.848,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"By -- precisely, by the machinery --","start":556.848,"stop":557.888,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1947 -- 1947?","start":557.888,"stop":561.538,"duration":3.65},{"text":"What happened?","start":561.538,"stop":562.222,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"When they got to him precisely --","start":562.222,"stop":563.942,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but --","start":563.942,"stop":564.532,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I do not know.","start":564.532,"stop":564.762,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and what was the upshot of that?","start":564.762,"stop":566.622,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The upshot of that was that he was --","start":566.622,"stop":568.802,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Clear?","start":568.802,"stop":569.092,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- clear.","start":569.092,"stop":569.842,"duration":0.75},{"text":"They found no doubt of his loyalty and they found that he was not a security risk.","start":569.842,"stop":573.995,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and he -- was he suspended during the --","start":573.995,"stop":576.425,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":576.425,"stop":576.915,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- State Department --","start":576.915,"stop":577.515,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":577.515,"stop":578.455,"duration":0.94},{"text":"No, he was --","start":578.455,"stop":578.575,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- until 1950 -- until the point you had reached when I interrupted you, until the Loyalty Board of the Civil Service Commission directed the State Department's Loyalty Board to reexamine if he had continuously continued in the Service of the State Department.","start":578.575,"stop":593.448,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":593.448,"stop":594.038,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":594.038,"stop":597.518,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"And so, when the Loyalty Review Board directed that the theretofore favorable findings of the State Department's Loyalty Security Board be reopened, they directed the State Department then to prefer charges against petitioner and to give him a hearing.","start":597.518,"stop":616.681,"duration":19.16},{"text":"And so, in March 1950, petitioner was on route to a new post in Kolkata.","start":616.681,"stop":623.291,"duration":6.61},{"text":"He was ordered to return to Washington where he was served with a formal charge by the Chairman of the State Department Loyalty Security Board, acting for the Secretary of State, charging that he was a security risk and that there was reason to believe him disloyal to the United States, because he was a member of the Communist Party and was an associate of improper persons.","start":623.291,"stop":654.721,"duration":31.43},{"text":"After a month of exhausted hearings interrupt --","start":654.721,"stop":656.701,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say -- did you say improper person or presence?","start":656.701,"stop":659.212,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Persons.","start":659.212,"stop":660.452,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":660.452,"stop":660.692,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I have characterized the substance of that charge.","start":660.692,"stop":665.412,"duration":4.72},{"text":"After about a month of hearings which were interrupted toward the end by hearing before a subcommittee of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, the Tydings subcommittee.","start":665.412,"stop":676.769,"duration":11.36},{"text":"The State Department Loyalty Board found in October 1950 that petitioner was neither disloyal nor a security risk.","start":676.769,"stop":686.339,"duration":9.57},{"text":"This finding was approved by the Deputy Under Secretary of State in accordance with the regulations thereafter.","start":686.339,"stop":695.249,"duration":8.91},{"text":"Thereafter, the Loyalty Review Board again assumed jurisdiction of the case on post-audit.","start":695.249,"stop":705.229,"duration":9.98},{"text":"And after holding the case for a while, returned it to the State Department for further reconsideration of some supplemental information which had been supplied.","start":705.229,"stop":714.739,"duration":9.51},{"text":"The State Department Board did reconsider it, reaffirmed its favorable finding, the Deputy Under Secretary approved the favorable findings and the case went back to the Loyalty Review Board.","start":714.739,"stop":727.039,"duration":12.3},{"text":"While it was there at this time, the President's Executive Order had been -- was amended to alter the standards for determining loyalty.","start":727.039,"stop":737.089,"duration":10.05},{"text":"And so, the case was returned to the State Department for a second reconsideration under the new standards of the Executive Order 10241.","start":737.089,"stop":747.88,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the date of that as to about?","start":747.88,"stop":752.198,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"It was after -- it was after the first of May and before the middle of July of 1950.","start":752.198,"stop":761.968,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"1950?","start":761.968,"stop":762.818,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":762.818,"stop":762.838,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":762.838,"stop":763.298,"duration":0.46},{"text":"All right.","start":763.298,"stop":764.008,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, 1951.","start":764.008,"stop":765.508,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"1951?","start":765.508,"stop":766.048,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":766.048,"stop":766.708,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":766.708,"stop":768.868,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"And at the end of July 1951, the Loyalty Security Board again reaffirmed its favorable decision, finding petitioner not to be of doubtful loyalty under the new standard.","start":768.868,"stop":786.348,"duration":17.48},{"text":"Thereafter, in mid October 1951, the Loyalty Review Board of the Civil Service Commission advised petitioner that a further hearing would be held in his case under that Board's regulation, Number 14, which has since been held at least in part invalid by this Court in Peters against Hobby.","start":786.348,"stop":812.812,"duration":26.46},{"text":"And a hearing was held on November the 8th, 1951.","start":812.812,"stop":818.342,"duration":5.53},{"text":"On December 13, 1951, the Loyalty Review Board notified petitioner that it had reversed the finding of the State Department Loyalty Security Board and found that there was a reasonable doubt of petitioner's loyalty.","start":818.342,"stop":838.453,"duration":20.11},{"text":"Now, this finding and purported a reversal of the State Department Board was not only rendered in what this Court has held to be a lawless assumption of jurisdiction.","start":838.453,"stop":855.379,"duration":16.93},{"text":"In our view, it grossly violated both the Executive Order and the Fifth Amendment in other respects.","start":855.379,"stop":863.588,"duration":8.21},{"text":"I have referred to the fact that petitioner's conversations with Jaffe were recorded by the FBI, both before the State Department Loyalty Security Board during his hearings there and before the Loyalty Review Board during his hearing there.","start":863.588,"stop":882.468,"duration":18.88},{"text":"Various questions were put to petitioner, which indicated that his judges had some kind of information as to what he was supposed to have said to Jaffe and Jaffe to him some five years earlier.","start":882.468,"stop":899.999,"duration":17.53},{"text":"But his request for access to whatever the Board's had in their possession was denied.","start":899.999,"stop":907.729,"duration":7.73},{"text":"The Loyalty Security Board of the State Department admitted that it did not have before it the texts, the exact texts of the FBI recordings of the conversations.","start":907.729,"stop":918.994,"duration":11.26},{"text":"And the Government in this litigation has admitted that there were no confidential informants involved in the case.","start":918.994,"stop":928.406,"duration":9.41},{"text":"And that petitioner's judges had before them only what purported to be summaries and digests of these conversations which had been wiretapped and recorded, but not the exact recordings, not the recordings themselves or any exact transcripts of them.","start":928.406,"stop":953.306,"duration":24.9},{"text":"Now, in this case, we know for a fact that these purported digests and summaries were highly inaccurate and unreliable because one of them, a purported transcript of the conversation of May 8, 1945 was shown to petitioner at a hearing before the Tydings subcommittee.","start":953.306,"stop":977.818,"duration":24.51},{"text":"This document which was exhibited to him and which is printed in the hearings of that subcommittee showed on its face that it was in many particulars highly inaccurate as a transcript of what the two men said to each other.","start":977.818,"stop":996.273,"duration":18.46},{"text":"And in other respects was and frankly labeled so unintelligent.","start":996.273,"stop":1003.233,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On its face, meaning just by reading it, you could tell me it was inaccurate.","start":1003.233,"stop":1005.385,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1005.385,"stop":1006.355,"duration":0.97},{"text":"In certain places, there was -- the transcriber simply put (Voice Overlap)","start":1006.355,"stop":1011.975,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand unintelligible but inaccurate.","start":1011.975,"stop":1014.421,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"In other places, the inaccuracy was apparent from the face of it plus any minimal knowledge of international affairs, because it had these two men saying things to each other, which was 180 degrees the opposite of what they would have said and anyone could tell.","start":1014.421,"stop":1034.929,"duration":20.51},{"text":"Finally, the Loyalty Review Board opinion which found petitioner to be of reasonably doubtful loyalty shows on its face that that Board relied in major part on these grossly inaccurate digests and summaries of the wiretap conversations in reaching their conclusion as to petitioner's loyalty.","start":1034.929,"stop":1060.65,"duration":25.72},{"text":"And that --","start":1060.65,"stop":1060.7,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And because of these various proceedings, Mr. Rhetts, was a specific request made by counsel for service for these documents on the basis of which the Civil Service Board acted?","start":1060.7,"stop":1073.807,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1073.807,"stop":1074.457,"duration":0.65},{"text":"And I should say there, Mr. Justice, that -- that that was done at page 2466 of the Tydings hearings, and there's an unfortunate inaccuracy in my brief, which refers to a different page where nothing like that occurred.","start":1074.457,"stop":1091.399,"duration":16.94},{"text":"The proper page in the Tydings hearing which is where the petitioner's Loyalty Board hearing is printed up, page 2466 of the appendix to the Tydings hearing.","start":1091.399,"stop":1104.894,"duration":13.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And I take it that you're putting this before us because in the chain of your argument, this becomes relevant as to the disposition and the sovereign considered --","start":1104.894,"stop":1115.964,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1115.964,"stop":1116.004,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- isn't that right?","start":1116.004,"stop":1116.934,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"This --","start":1116.934,"stop":1117.554,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that this question is relevant.","start":1117.554,"stop":1119.014,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"This question is relevant as I shall very shortly point out.","start":1119.014,"stop":1123.891,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What page on your brief issued that correction?","start":1123.891,"stop":1126.331,"duration":2.44},{"text":"Go on just see.","start":1126.331,"stop":1128.061,"duration":1.73},{"text":"Was it -- well, don't bother if you haven't got the page.","start":1128.061,"stop":1130.607,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I can give it to you.","start":1130.607,"stop":1134.547,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":1134.547,"stop":1134.917,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we think it plain therefore that both the Executive or the Loyalty Executive Order and the Fifth Amendment --","start":1134.917,"stop":1143.842,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 22.","start":1143.842,"stop":1145.862,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- required not only that petitioner have an opportunity to meet the evidence against him, to explain it and to refute it if he could but that his judges have access to the evidence on the basis of which they presumed to judge.","start":1145.862,"stop":1163.458,"duration":17.6},{"text":"And we maintain that both the Executive Order and the Fifth Amendment require that.","start":1163.458,"stop":1170.908,"duration":7.45},{"text":"Well, these were the circumstances under which the Loyalty Review Board purported to reverse the favorable finding of the State Department Board.","start":1170.908,"stop":1182.837,"duration":11.93},{"text":"And on the same day that the Loyalty Review Board announced its decision, the Secretary of State executed its mandate by dismissing petitioner after 16 years about standing performance in the Foreign Service.","start":1182.837,"stop":1200.49,"duration":17.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that the act of dismissal which was the basis of this proceeding?","start":1200.49,"stop":1204.26,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the action of which we complain.","start":1204.26,"stop":1208.986,"duration":4.73},{"text":"Now, the first major ground on which we rest our claim that this action was invalid is that by relying solely on this unlawful and invalid finding of the Loyalty Review Board as the basis for his determination to discharge petitioner.","start":1208.986,"stop":1230.379,"duration":21.39},{"text":"The Secretary's dismissal action represented at best an arbitrary exercise of his discretion, which under the decisions of this Court in Perkins against Elg and later cases was to be set aside as invalid.","start":1230.379,"stop":1247.676,"duration":17.3},{"text":"Now, there is no question here but that the unlawful finding of the Loyalty Review Board does in fact constitute the sole basis for the Secretary's exercise of his discretion.","start":1247.676,"stop":1264.857,"duration":17.18}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you say that again?","start":1264.857,"stop":1266.007,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I say there is no question here in this case but that the unlawful finding of the Loyalty Review Board constitutes the sole basis for the Secretary's action.","start":1266.007,"stop":1281.527,"duration":15.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that conceded in the theory?","start":1281.527,"stop":1284.232,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"We have his own statement in his affidavit.","start":1284.232,"stop":1287.522,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I mean did the Government concede that?","start":1287.522,"stop":1289.592,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1289.592,"stop":1291.192,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or could he have taken this action out of the air without ever looking at what the Loyalty Board did?","start":1291.192,"stop":1298.825,"duration":7.63},{"text":"I mean as a matter of law, as a matter of power.","start":1298.825,"stop":1300.905,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Putting aside -- putting aside an independent difficulty that we have in this case, had it -- under the statute had he never issued any regulations to govern himself.","start":1300.905,"stop":1313.907,"duration":13},{"text":"I will concede that he could have simply thought about of the blue that it was in the interest of the United States.","start":1313.907,"stop":1319.665,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"His own observation -- his own observation --","start":1319.665,"stop":1322.035,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1322.035,"stop":1322.735,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"To discuss of a man's judgment.","start":1322.735,"stop":1324.485,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1324.485,"stop":1324.635,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm asking.","start":1324.635,"stop":1325.165,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I don't know.","start":1325.165,"stop":1326.115,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Could he as a matter of power under the statute?","start":1326.115,"stop":1328.685,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the statute he --","start":1328.685,"stop":1328.805,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then the Secretary of State --","start":1328.805,"stop":1329.635,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- certainly could.","start":1329.635,"stop":1330.635,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- say, \"All right, this fellow's judgment is not for this kind of work.\"","start":1330.635,"stop":1335.15,"duration":4.52},{"text":"Now, what you say is he didn't do that and since he gave a reason, his action must be judged by his reason.","start":1335.15,"stop":1341.709,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1341.709,"stop":1343.319,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Now, he gave his reason in an affidavit which he supplied to the Government after this litigation commenced.","start":1343.319,"stop":1351.659,"duration":8.34},{"text":"It appears at -- commencing it on page 8 --","start":1351.659,"stop":1353.679,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they supply with a reference?","start":1353.679,"stop":1355.889,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is to say the Government requested him for an affidavit as in support of its motion for summary judgment papers.","start":1355.889,"stop":1363.045,"duration":7.16},{"text":"On its --","start":1363.045,"stop":1363.065,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1363.065,"stop":1363.865,"duration":0.8},{"text":"-- by way of affidavit?","start":1363.865,"stop":1365.385,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1365.385,"stop":1365.955,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1365.955,"stop":1366.845,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 82 of the record, paragraph 5 of his affidavit, he refers to his determination to discharge the petitioner.","start":1366.845,"stop":1378.389,"duration":11.54},{"text":"And he says, \"I made that determination, solely as the result of the finding of the Loyalty Review Board.","start":1378.389,"stop":1390.099,"duration":11.71},{"text":"I did not make any independent determination of my own as to whether on the evidence submitted before those Boards there was a reasonable doubt of Mr. Service's loyalty.","start":1390.099,"stop":1400.619,"duration":10.52},{"text":"I made no independent judgment on the record in this case.\"","start":1400.619,"stop":1408.719,"duration":8.1},{"text":"Now, it is our position that an exercise of executive discretion resting as the Secretary so handedly states, “This one did solely on such a wholly unlawful foundation, constitutes an abuse of discretion or an arbitrary exercise of discretion in violation of the Fifth Amendment.”","start":1408.719,"stop":1431.096,"duration":22.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the next step mean in the Secretary's -- the ex-Secretary's affidavit?","start":1431.096,"stop":1437.286,"duration":6.19},{"text":"There was nothing on page -- there was nothing in the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board, which would make it incompatible with the exercise of my responsibility, the Secretary of State.","start":1437.286,"stop":1448.364,"duration":11.08},{"text":"What does that mean?","start":1448.364,"stop":1449.694,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I've had some difficulty in understanding precisely what that means.","start":1449.694,"stop":1454.684,"duration":4.99},{"text":"I -- I assume that it meant that on its face, the --","start":1454.684,"stop":1459.293,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He was asked to do something that the law prepared, I assume.","start":1459.293,"stop":1462.033,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1462.033,"stop":1463.373,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Indeed -- indeed, my -- my -- it is my -- I suggest that either he acted on -- he acted on one or two assumptions.","start":1463.373,"stop":1474.333,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Now, the law -- the Government contends for example that he makes clear that he did not act on the assumption that he was legally required to follow the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board.","start":1474.333,"stop":1489.493,"duration":15.16},{"text":"Now, there's -- despite considerable contemporaneous evidence to the contrary, we accept his assertion in his affidavit that he did not deemed himself legally required to do so.","start":1489.493,"stop":1502.099,"duration":12.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the next sentence --","start":1502.099,"stop":1502.699,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"But we --","start":1502.699,"stop":1502.999,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was that.","start":1502.999,"stop":1503.539,"duration":0.54},{"text":"The next -- the sentence after the one we've just been talking about, I deemed it appropriate advisable to act on the basis of the finding and opinion of the Loyalty Review Board.","start":1503.539,"stop":1513.149,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That becomes clear at the top of page 83.","start":1513.149,"stop":1515.779,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That he found himself legally.","start":1515.779,"stop":1517.562,"duration":1.78},{"text":"He -- he was not required to but he found himself legally free to do so.","start":1517.562,"stop":1522.502,"duration":4.94},{"text":"Now, our position is that he was -- that that is the misapprehension which we complain.","start":1522.502,"stop":1531.062,"duration":8.56},{"text":"He was not legally free to do so.","start":1531.062,"stop":1534.102,"duration":3.04},{"text":"Now, I -- I suggest to you that that is the demonstrable in these terms.","start":1534.102,"stop":1539.776,"duration":5.67},{"text":"Either he acted on the assumption that the opinion and finding of the Loyalty Review Board was a valid one, a lawful one or he acted on the assumption that whether it was valid and lawful or not, he was free to rest his --","start":1539.776,"stop":1563.412,"duration":23.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, these are a lot words we'd say.","start":1563.412,"stop":1565.122,"duration":1.71},{"text":"Although, I was illegally bound, in fact I did.","start":1565.122,"stop":1567.682,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact, I did and I relied on this and nothing else.","start":1567.682,"stop":1571.737,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr Rhetts, right there.","start":1571.737,"stop":1573.537,"duration":1.8},{"text":"I gather the very first sentence of paragraph 5.","start":1573.537,"stop":1577.647,"duration":4.11},{"text":"It reads, “I made that determination solely as the result of the findings and so forth.”","start":1577.647,"stop":1583.087,"duration":5.44},{"text":"Your reading -- I made that determination solely because of the finding of it.","start":1583.087,"stop":1587.797,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1587.797,"stop":1588.347,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's where you're reading it --","start":1588.347,"stop":1589.257,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1589.257,"stop":1589.487,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- isn't it?","start":1589.487,"stop":1591.657,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it that the following language would support that where he says, “I -- I made no -- I did not -- in making this determination, I did not read the testimony.","start":1591.657,"stop":1605.656,"duration":14},{"text":"I made no independent judgment on the record.”","start":1605.656,"stop":1608.866,"duration":3.21},{"text":"I assume what he is saying is that I looked to the Loyalty Review Board opinion alone and relying exclusively on that, I reached the conclusion that was appropriate and advisable to terminate.","start":1608.866,"stop":1619.446,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't read that.","start":1619.446,"stop":1619.846,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that -- that --","start":1619.846,"stop":1620.476,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't read that paragraph.","start":1620.476,"stop":1622.436,"duration":1.96},{"text":"When I asked you the question that namely, a little while ago, whether out of the blue or in his judgment or for reasons that can't be put into words, subject of course, the Secretary of State could -- could sever employment.","start":1622.436,"stop":1636.956,"duration":14.52},{"text":"Your answer was --","start":1636.956,"stop":1637.496,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I have no question.","start":1637.496,"stop":1638.356,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1638.356,"stop":1639.066,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1639.066,"stop":1639.606,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what this mean is that -- that there a lot words to say.","start":1639.606,"stop":1643.279,"duration":3.67},{"text":"I could not have been mandamus to do this.","start":1643.279,"stop":1645.999,"duration":2.72},{"text":"I wasn't violating any of my responsibility to the Secretary of State.","start":1645.999,"stop":1649.539,"duration":3.54},{"text":"In fact, what I did, I did because the Loyalty Board recommended this.","start":1649.539,"stop":1653.289,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that -- that is why -- how I read the -- and I would not --","start":1653.289,"stop":1656.299,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose -- I suppose that sentence later on in which he said there was nothing in the opinion of the Loyalty Review Board which could make it incompatible with the exercise of my responsibilities as Secretary of State to act on it implies that he did.","start":1656.299,"stop":1672.625,"duration":16.33},{"text":"In fact, acted on it and it alone --","start":1672.625,"stop":1674.055,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"It alone.","start":1674.055,"stop":1674.075,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is that it?","start":1674.075,"stop":1674.695,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"And it seems to me either by reciting the various things that he did not do such as make a judgment on the record and the whole.","start":1674.695,"stop":1681.739,"duration":7.04},{"text":"He -- he is saying that I look to this opinion and because it purported to reverse my Board.","start":1681.739,"stop":1688.099,"duration":6.36},{"text":"I deemed it appropriate to discharge him without further consideration, the merits or anything else by it.","start":1688.099,"stop":1696.108,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you saying legally that if -- if he said in explicit words, if he said in terminating the service of -- the employment of his service, “I acted on my discretion as Secretary of State,” you wouldn't be here.","start":1696.108,"stop":1711.078,"duration":14.97}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is correct.","start":1711.078,"stop":1712.388,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You're here because he -- he precisely did not say that and said the opposite to wit.","start":1712.388,"stop":1718.303,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm --","start":1718.303,"stop":1718.603,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I felt free to act on that and I did act on that.","start":1718.603,"stop":1722.686,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I must -- except one thing, if they were not for another matter which I will come to shortly, some regulations.","start":1722.686,"stop":1727.996,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1727.996,"stop":1728.586,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"But at the time, the statute had been passed, had he never issued any regulations and had he said, “I deem it in the advisable and the interest of the United States to discharge this petitioner without any hearing, without anything else.”","start":1728.586,"stop":1742.336,"duration":13.75},{"text":"He'd been perfectly free to do so, but he did not do that.","start":1742.336,"stop":1748.036,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And may I -- may I, Mr. Rhetts, taking the very last sentence and I gather you suggest that that last sentence if there's any possible inference from it that there were other considerations than merely the finding of the Loyalty Review Board, you can't read them into that sentence in light of the context which precedes it.","start":1748.036,"stop":1768.43,"duration":20.39}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my belief as to what a fair reading of this affidavit is.","start":1768.43,"stop":1776.86,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Now --","start":1776.86,"stop":1777.19,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you're arguing that the affidavit of Acheson is inconsistent with the -- with the press release governing the discharge?","start":1777.19,"stop":1785.781,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suggest that it is inconsistent but I'm not relying on the press release anymore.","start":1785.781,"stop":1790.231,"duration":4.45},{"text":"I accept his assertion, his statement that he was -- he was not -- he didn't think he was required to follow the Loyalty Review Board.","start":1790.231,"stop":1800.184,"duration":9.95},{"text":"He says that here and I accept that.","start":1800.184,"stop":1803.474,"duration":3.29},{"text":"But he did say that he was free to do so and I deny that he was free to do so.","start":1803.474,"stop":1812.131,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose he had said it, would it make a difference Mr. Rhetts, if the Secretary is -- was then the Secretary had said, “Under the law, I have power to exercise my independent judgment about any officer's continuance in the Foreign Service,” if this man was in the Foreign Service.","start":1812.131,"stop":1831.516,"duration":19.38},{"text":"I haven't got time to exercise my discretion and the only self-respecting way which I could, namely, to read all the testimony, to inform myself, to listen to my people practically consider the committing magistrate.","start":1831.516,"stop":1844.497,"duration":12.98},{"text":"I just haven't got time.","start":1844.497,"stop":1846.227,"duration":1.73},{"text":"When was it, 1951, 1953, some other things, what have you?","start":1846.227,"stop":1849.717,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I therefore didn't exercise an independent discretion but I exercised my discretion by taking the word of the Loyalty Review Board, could that be all right?","start":1849.717,"stop":1859.503,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that's what he -- that's what he did do without putting in that he didn't have time to do it, but I say -- I say he's not free at all.","start":1859.503,"stop":1865.943,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But","start":1865.943,"stop":1866.523,"duration":0.58},{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1866.523,"stop":1867.493,"duration":0.97},{"text":"-- since I could do it as it were arbitrarily, I can let -- the Loyalty Review Board have made the findings for me.","start":1867.493,"stop":1874.024,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"But I do not -- I do not think he could do it arbitrarily.","start":1874.024,"stop":1877.664,"duration":3.64},{"text":"And of course --","start":1877.664,"stop":1877.754,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But he could do it without giving any reason.","start":1877.754,"stop":1879.634,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1879.634,"stop":1879.784,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't give a bad reason --","start":1879.784,"stop":1880.934,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1880.934,"stop":1881.224,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- about the early cases, the Elg case.","start":1881.224,"stop":1883.247,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1883.247,"stop":1883.847,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't give a reason that's no good.","start":1883.847,"stop":1886.117,"duration":2.27},{"text":"But if he doesn't give any reasons, then presumably he must have acted on allowable reasons.","start":1886.117,"stop":1890.977,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is -- seems to me is the difference between the assumption that he did it arbitrarily.","start":1890.977,"stop":1894.383,"duration":3.41},{"text":"I -- I take it, the law would be clear that he could not do it arbitrarily.","start":1894.383,"stop":1898.303,"duration":3.92},{"text":"On the other hand, he is not required.","start":1898.303,"stop":1900.673,"duration":2.37},{"text":"He would -- here, he could act and not be required to give his reasons and the law would presume that he had --","start":1900.673,"stop":1907.712,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if he gave it, he can give reasons that are not sustainable as an exercise of reasonable discretion.","start":1907.712,"stop":1912.582,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1912.582,"stop":1913.542,"duration":0.96},{"text":"That's our position.","start":1913.542,"stop":1922.695,"duration":9.15},{"text":"And I -- I think -- I think there is no point in going further.","start":1922.695,"stop":1931.862,"duration":9.17},{"text":"That is our position.","start":1931.862,"stop":1932.882,"duration":1.02},{"text":"That is what the Elg case teaches and teaches properly.","start":1932.882,"stop":1938.862,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it have made -- would it make a difference in your view if he had appointed his own ad hoc, an ad hoc board a clear part to distinguish ex-Ambassadors to advise them and they had brought in a report, a report and he had -- had acted on their report and said, “I haven't got time to go into this thing, indeed just like a master in chancery and I have doubt their report without having read their testimony.”","start":1938.862,"stop":1971.097,"duration":32.23}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, indeed, his regulations which is a branch of the case, I would turn to next to provide substantially in that -- along that line, not a group outside distinguishes but it provides a mechanism which does not require him personally.","start":1971.097,"stop":1985.866,"duration":14.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's a different point, namely, that he has the erected your -- your suggestion is that -- the point you're about to urge is that there was erected an administrative departmental procedure to which he must be bound because he enunciated it as such.","start":1985.866,"stop":2001.106,"duration":15.24},{"text":"He can't waive it ad hoc.","start":2001.106,"stop":2002.506,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2002.506,"stop":2003.086,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2003.086,"stop":2005.266,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I take it though, Mr. Rhetts.","start":2005.266,"stop":2007.731,"duration":2.46},{"text":"You rely rather heavily here on the infirmities as you see them in the proceedings before this Loyalty Review Board.","start":2007.731,"stop":2015.813,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2015.813,"stop":2015.993,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Which if they existed in the case that Mr. Justice Frankfurter put to you would probably have you here making the same argument you're making today.","start":2015.993,"stop":2026.483,"duration":10.49},{"text":"If that --","start":2026.483,"stop":2026.603,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm --","start":2026.603,"stop":2026.663,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was the same kind of infirmities in the proceedings before the special board that Mr. Justice Frankfurter suggested --","start":2026.663,"stop":2034.112,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2034.112,"stop":2034.192,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- might have been employed.","start":2034.192,"stop":2035.382,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":2035.382,"stop":2035.772,"duration":0.39},{"text":"Had there been any special board created, and it acted in such a way, acted even properly, and the Secretary relied solely on that, I would equally be here today.","start":2035.772,"stop":2048.86,"duration":13.09},{"text":"And this is why, Mr. Justice, in response to your question a while ago, I think, that the deficiencies of the Loyalty Review Board findings here are not merely, and I don't mean by this to minimize, not merely the technical exceeding of its jurisdiction.","start":2048.86,"stop":2068.415,"duration":19.55},{"text":"But there are substantive deficiencies in the action so that those -- the action of those men cannot be deemed as just the volunteer of opinion of three distinguished men.","start":2068.415,"stop":2080.666,"duration":12.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We never have those questions and have reached those questions in the Peters' case.","start":2080.666,"stop":2084.326,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2084.326,"stop":2084.406,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We did not reach those questions in Peters.","start":2084.406,"stop":2085.826,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I -- and that is why I say these additional deficiencies to which I referred, namely, the use of -- the improper use of -- of this material to which the petitioner never had an opportunity to -- to refute and the improper use of material upon which his judges judge him, judged, vitiated their action even if you conceive of them as three private individuals to whom he might have turned to in a volunteered capacity.","start":2085.826,"stop":2117.596,"duration":31.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps, I've got to wait until we hear from the Government, but is there anything in the Government's brief which agrees that to where those deficiencies is not whether or not they did --","start":2117.596,"stop":2126.546,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":2126.546,"stop":2126.686,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- initiated the determination --","start":2126.686,"stop":2128.496,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"They --","start":2128.496,"stop":2130.336,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that whether those -- do they disagree with you upon the existence of those deficiency?","start":2130.336,"stop":2134.847,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2134.847,"stop":2135.177,"duration":0.33},{"text":"They -- they concede that the -- that there was the deficiency as to the jurisdiction.","start":2135.177,"stop":2141.475,"duration":6.3},{"text":"That is they agree that the Loyalty Review Board had no jurisdiction.","start":2141.475,"stop":2144.765,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Peters and Hobby.","start":2144.765,"stop":2145.755,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Peters and Hobby.","start":2145.755,"stop":2147.795,"duration":2.04},{"text":"They do not concede that there is anything wrong with refusing petitioner the opportunity to see the material which he -- was being used against him nor do they concede that there'd be anything wrong, in fact that his judges had access to nothing more than these summaries of inadequate materials as we could see them.","start":2147.795,"stop":2175.979,"duration":28.18},{"text":"Well, now, turning to the second and independent ground on which we base our contention as to the invalidity of this dismissal.","start":2175.979,"stop":2188.994,"duration":13.02},{"text":"It is important to commence here, but I should say as Mr. Justice Frankfurter said, our position here is that the Secretary violated regulations which he himself imposed on himself to control his -- as to the manner in which he would exercise his absolute discretion under the McCarran Rider.","start":2188.994,"stop":2215.588,"duration":26.59},{"text":"Now, on this phase of the case, the place we start is the formal letter of charges which was preferred against him and which appears beginning at page 28 of the record, which was the commencement of the proceeding.","start":2215.588,"stop":2237.848,"duration":22.26},{"text":"Now, this letter of charges which was dated March 24, 1950, first referred to the President's Loyalty Order and then to the regulations and procedures promulgated on March 11 by the State Department, and stating that a copy of these regulations was enclosed.","start":2237.848,"stop":2260.067,"duration":22.22},{"text":"The letter then refer -- preferred specific charges against the petitioner under specified sections of these regulations.","start":2260.067,"stop":2267.834,"duration":7.77},{"text":"And then, it advised petitioner that a hearing had been scheduled under Section 395 of these regulations, and I'm reading at the bottom of page 29, “To consider this charge with a view to making a recommendation to the Sectary of State whether or not under the provisions of the Department of State Appropriation Act, etcetera, your employment in the Department should be terminated in the interest of United States.”","start":2267.834,"stop":2300.143,"duration":32.31},{"text":"Now, then, the -- the statute to which reference is there made and the language which is used is what is commonly called the McCarran Rider.","start":2300.143,"stop":2304.193,"duration":4.05},{"text":"And the language quoted is a verbatim \"from the McCarran Rider,\" a Rider which was annually attached to the State Department Appropriation Act for a number of years.","start":2304.193,"stop":2323.731,"duration":19.54},{"text":"The letter of charges then goes on to fix a date for hearing, invites a reply to the charges and offers to give further details of the charges orally.","start":2323.731,"stop":2336.051,"duration":12.32},{"text":"Now, we submit that on any fair view of the matter, this formal letter of charges, which in its accusation and its consequences is so much like a criminal indictment.","start":2336.051,"stop":2349.514,"duration":13.46},{"text":"It must be regarded as establishing the framework, procedural and substantive for all the subsequent proceeding.","start":2349.514,"stop":2359.324,"duration":9.81},{"text":"As plainly as language can make it, it said, “We are going to give you a hearing to determine whether under the McCarran Rider, your dismissal is necessary or advisable in the interest of the United States.","start":2359.324,"stop":2372.394,"duration":13.07},{"text":"And it said, “The answer to this question will depend in turn on whether you are found to be of doubtful loyalty or a security risk.","start":2372.394,"stop":2382.844,"duration":10.45},{"text":"We're going to try you under regulations of March 11, 1949.","start":2382.844,"stop":2387.537,"duration":4.69},{"text":"We here with furnish you a copy of them so that from these, you may ascertain first what the charges are against you, and what the rules of your trial will be.","start":2387.537,"stop":2398.162,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that, the doctrine at the record?","start":2398.162,"stop":2400.022,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Page -- commencing at the bottom of page 28, Exhibit B.","start":2400.022,"stop":2408.269,"duration":8.25},{"text":"It runs on to page 30.","start":2408.269,"stop":2411.569,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Now, turning to these regulations themselves and there set forth commencing at pages 61 of the appendix to our brief, they establish, first, substantive standards and procedural rules relating to loyalty adjudications under the Loyalty Executive Order.","start":2411.569,"stop":2436.33,"duration":24.76},{"text":"The second category of substantive standards laid down on the so-called security principles and the regulations regarding this provide at page 61 and 62 of our appendix, Section 391.3.","start":2436.33,"stop":2457.02,"duration":20.69},{"text":"In addition, the Secretary of State has been granted by Congress the right in his absolute discretion to terminate the employment and so on.","start":2457.02,"stop":2466.921,"duration":9.9},{"text":"That is a verbatim quotation from the McCarran Rider and we turn the page and then they say, “In the exercise of this right, the Department will so far as possible afford its employees the same protection as those provided under the Executive Order.","start":2466.921,"stop":2487.578,"duration":20.66},{"text":"And the regulations proceed to do just that.","start":2487.578,"stop":2492.03,"duration":4.45},{"text":"So far as they're relevant here, they first provide that if the Loyalty Security Board, the State Department, if its decision is favorable to the employee and if that decision is confirmed by the Deputy Assistant Secretary for Administration, he will so notify the employee, and the case is closed.","start":2492.03,"stop":2517.818,"duration":25.79},{"text":"In this case, the petitioner received such favorable decisions from the lawyer of the Security Board, three different times.","start":2517.818,"stop":2526.018,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Under the regulations therefore, the case should have been ended after the first of these favorable decisions.","start":2526.018,"stop":2535.472,"duration":9.45},{"text":"Instead, the Loyalty Review Board twice caused the case to be reopened and after the second of this, the Secretary of State interposed his own adverse determination in violation of his own regulation.","start":2535.472,"stop":2550.633,"duration":15.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When were these regulations promulgated by the Secretary of State?","start":2550.633,"stop":2553.513,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"March 11, 1949.","start":2553.513,"stop":2556.173,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"March 11, 1949.","start":2556.173,"stop":2557.743,"duration":1.57},{"text":"And how long did they subsist as they were?","start":2557.743,"stop":2562.334,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"They were subsequently amended on May 4th, 1951, and again on September 21, 1951.","start":2562.334,"stop":2570.673,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Amended in matters that would have made it -- made it an important matter affecting this case?","start":2570.673,"stop":2578.732,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government contends so, we contend not.","start":2578.732,"stop":2581.682,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that an issue there as to --","start":2581.682,"stop":2582.992,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is an issue which --","start":2582.992,"stop":2583.992,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay, and let me ask you this.","start":2583.992,"stop":2587.432,"duration":3.44},{"text":"Such as they were these regulations, is it a matter of judicial knowledge or concession that -- that a number of officials in the Department were a judge that this was a procedure followed in X number of cases?","start":2587.432,"stop":2607.811,"duration":20.38},{"text":"Let me also ask you differently.","start":2607.811,"stop":2609.121,"duration":1.31},{"text":"Was this the -- the procedure outlined in Section 3922 (f) and it -- emendation of changes, was that the normal procedure in the State Department for handling matters of this sort?","start":2609.121,"stop":2622.151,"duration":13.03}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as I know, there has been no suggestion to the contrary that that was normal.","start":2622.151,"stop":2627.261,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It is fair to say then that this was an ad hoc way of dealing with the situation.","start":2627.261,"stop":2632.381,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The one --","start":2632.381,"stop":2632.551,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2632.551,"stop":2633.301,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The one ultimately adopted in this case.","start":2633.301,"stop":2635.009,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that -- that the way in which Service --","start":2635.009,"stop":2636.379,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Even to that part, a contention, yes.","start":2636.379,"stop":2638.229,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the way with Service, the connection was finally terminated out of the current of that which you say the regulations provide.","start":2638.229,"stop":2648.227,"duration":10}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":2648.227,"stop":2648.967,"duration":0.74},{"text":"It was -- it was --","start":2648.967,"stop":2649.897,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Out of a current of what was in fact done in other cases.","start":2649.897,"stop":2652.797,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't say what was in fact on in other cases but it's certainly departed from the regulations.","start":2652.797,"stop":2658.655,"duration":5.86},{"text":"That is to say and my position is that the petitioner here was tried under the regulations, also to that --","start":2658.655,"stop":2663.845,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Regulations purport to deal with the case --","start":2663.845,"stop":2666.025,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"And the regulations as I have just said purport to be issued under the McCarran Rider, and he was given a hearing, and he was tried under these regulations.","start":2666.025,"stop":2676.346,"duration":10.32},{"text":"These were the regulations supplied to him.","start":2676.346,"stop":2678.866,"duration":2.52},{"text":"The only copy he ever had was tendered to him as a part of his formal letter of charges.","start":2678.866,"stop":2683.556,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. --","start":2683.556,"stop":2683.736,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, let me ask you this question.","start":2683.736,"stop":2685.021,"duration":1.29},{"text":"Could the Secretary of State has said that the Loyalty Board of the Civil Service Commission, not that I do not follow your conclusion or I think if I overrule it, but you're in an intrusive body.","start":2685.021,"stop":2696.594,"duration":11.57},{"text":"You have nothing to do with my determination.","start":2696.594,"stop":2699.734,"duration":3.14},{"text":"I don't need his ultimate legal right but we have a system authorized by law for disposing of so-called loyalty cases and this is none of your business.","start":2699.734,"stop":2708.452,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Is that -- had been within the statute in the regulation?","start":2708.452,"stop":2712.492,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is exactly what the regulations required and I sought not.","start":2712.492,"stop":2715.212,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position?","start":2715.212,"stop":2716.372,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's my position and we sought an opportunity to press it on the Secretary of State at the time before denying it.","start":2716.372,"stop":2721.776,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rhetts, where is the provision if there is one?","start":2721.776,"stop":2724.656,"duration":2.88},{"text":"I find 394.12 at page 80, is this it, “Dealing with a clearly favorable conclusion that shall so determine and notify the Deputy Under Secretary through Administration?”","start":2724.656,"stop":2735.288,"duration":10.63},{"text":"Is that the one which you say, “It says that that shall be the end of the matter,” or is there another?","start":2735.288,"stop":2740.21,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't get where you were referring to.","start":2740.21,"stop":2741.46,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- I'm looking at page 80, 394.12 at the bottom of the page.","start":2741.46,"stop":2748.505,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"As I think the trouble there, Mr. Justice Brennan, is that you're now into --","start":2748.505,"stop":2753.855,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Something --","start":2753.855,"stop":2754.065,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the later version of the regulation.","start":2754.065,"stop":2755.595,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I'm looking for is --","start":2755.595,"stop":2756.882,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is one place it says it in the later version and I rely on that so far as the earlier version, the March 12 regulations.","start":2756.882,"stop":2766.555,"duration":9.67},{"text":"That appears at -- in --","start":2766.555,"stop":2778.355,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I want particularly is --","start":2778.355,"stop":2779.985,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 390.","start":2779.985,"stop":2781.005,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to those provisions, which say that when there is a clearly favorable conclusion, that shall be the end of the matter which I think is what you suggested?","start":2781.005,"stop":2789.002,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2789.002,"stop":2789.472,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Well, that appears -- commencing at the bottom of page 69.","start":2789.472,"stop":2793.454,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"69?","start":2793.454,"stop":2794.134,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"See, the trouble is we have two sets of regulations.","start":2794.134,"stop":2796.134,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2796.134,"stop":2796.894,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"You put your finger on the version of the later regulations, which the Government contends are controlling, and I contend that point that you referred to favors this.","start":2796.894,"stop":2807.994,"duration":11.1},{"text":"The earlier regulations, commences at the bottom of page 69 and says that “Upon recede of the record including the decision of the Loyalty Security Board, if the Assistant Secretary -- that the decision of the Loyalty Security Board is favorable to the officer or employee concerned and is to heard in by the Assistant Secretary, he will notify the officer or employee.”","start":2807.994,"stop":2831.93,"duration":23.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, that's what I want to get to.","start":2831.93,"stop":2833.28,"duration":1.35},{"text":"So, there was in fact a concurrence required?","start":2833.28,"stop":2835.85,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2835.85,"stop":2836.44,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":2836.44,"stop":2837.05,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That was given here.","start":2837.05,"stop":2837.93,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that was given.","start":2837.93,"stop":2838.834,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2838.834,"stop":2838.904,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And each of the three -- on each of the three occasion?","start":2838.904,"stop":2841.294,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No question about that.","start":2841.294,"stop":2842.654,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And had the -- had there been a revision of this requirement in anywise before the second or third --","start":2842.654,"stop":2850.994,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you have put your finger on the -- on the --","start":2850.994,"stop":2853.734,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Second?","start":2853.734,"stop":2854.124,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on the related -- on the comparable provision applicable under the later version.","start":2854.124,"stop":2859.094,"duration":4.97},{"text":"There, the only difference -- there, it said that in the event of a favorable decision by the Loyalty Security Board, if the decision is on question of loyalty, the later regulations that you just referred to, say if the decision is to loyalty he should be -- the employee must be notified that the loyalty decision is subject to post-audit by the Loyalty Review Board.","start":2859.094,"stop":2882.17,"duration":23.08},{"text":"Now, we know from the decision of this Court that post-audit cannot extend to reversal of a favorable decision of the State Department Board.","start":2882.17,"stop":2892.09,"duration":9.92},{"text":"And so, you'll come to the same place.","start":2892.09,"stop":2894.89,"duration":2.8},{"text":"You can post-audit all you like but you can't reverse a favorable decision.","start":2894.89,"stop":2899.5,"duration":4.61},{"text":"And so, again --","start":2899.5,"stop":2900.41,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the Government -- does the Government challenge the file of the Secretary to promulgate these regulations validly?","start":2900.41,"stop":2910.138,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the courts below have so held.","start":2910.138,"stop":2913.878,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They claimed that these were beyond the powers of the Secretary --","start":2913.878,"stop":2916.578,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2916.578,"stop":2916.668,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to give them this kind of a hearing?","start":2916.668,"stop":2918.328,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2918.328,"stop":2919.818,"duration":1.49},{"text":"The Government makes both those contention.","start":2919.818,"stop":2923.857,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that different between this than in the accorded regulation.","start":2923.857,"stop":2927.667,"duration":3.81},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2927.667,"stop":2927.887,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it so because --","start":2927.887,"stop":2928.857,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if they challenge him here?","start":2928.857,"stop":2930.227,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's right.","start":2930.227,"stop":2931.765,"duration":1.54},{"text":"The Government makes two contentions which I'll -- which I will come to.","start":2931.765,"stop":2937.555,"duration":5.79},{"text":"I think I might as well pass any argument on the proposition that this later version of -- of regulation, we maintained they were not -- the later version was not applicable.","start":2937.555,"stop":2951.309,"duration":13.75},{"text":"That is the September 21, 1951, regulations were not applicable to this case because he was tried under the March 14, 1959 -- 1949 regulation.","start":2951.309,"stop":2963.769,"duration":12.46},{"text":"The later version was promulgated after his trial was all over, and we say that they may not be retroactively applied to the decision of this case, which plaintiff was represented to him that he would be tried under the 1949 legislation.","start":2963.769,"stop":2983.202,"duration":19.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as a matter -- as to the fact though, Mr. Rhetts, were either the second or third determination, clearances subsequent to the revision in this regard?","start":2983.202,"stop":2996.093,"duration":12.89},{"text":"You said he was tried under the March, but I think you said earlier, there were three separate --","start":2996.093,"stop":3002.743,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"The regulations have been first amended in May 1951.","start":3002.743,"stop":3008.2,"duration":5.46},{"text":"The second reconsideration by the Loyalty Security Board under the new standard, but no hearing, just a reconsideration was in July 31.","start":3008.2,"stop":3018.588,"duration":10.39},{"text":"So, to that extent, that action occurred after the first of the amendment.","start":3018.588,"stop":3023.901,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what is to the third one?","start":3023.901,"stop":3025.531,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No action except the final action of the Secretary, discharge the petition.","start":3025.531,"stop":3031.131,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rhett, I have -- I have been greatly puzzled since I heard your answer to Mr. Justice Black.","start":3031.131,"stop":3037.571,"duration":6.44},{"text":"I'd never get that as I haven't read the brief.","start":3037.571,"stop":3039.974,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Did I understand you to say the Government contends that the Secretary, although, on the statute he had -- could exercise a discretion by -- all on his own?","start":3039.974,"stop":3049.251,"duration":9.28},{"text":"Has a power to issue a scheme of a procedure or dealing with a claim that's suspicious on his own?","start":3049.251,"stop":3058.984,"duration":9.73},{"text":"Is that ultra vires?","start":3058.984,"stop":3060.604,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3060.604,"stop":3062.094,"duration":1.49},{"text":"That is the --","start":3062.094,"stop":3062.344,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because of the -- because there is a -- a presidential order --","start":3062.344,"stop":3066.494,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3066.494,"stop":3066.514,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of this scheme --","start":3066.514,"stop":3067.374,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Because --","start":3067.374,"stop":3067.764,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3067.764,"stop":3069.454,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Because they maintained.","start":3069.454,"stop":3070.724,"duration":1.27},{"text":"Congress did not intend that the Secretary should in anyway better --","start":3070.724,"stop":3076.244,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"His own?","start":3076.244,"stop":3076.754,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- his own exercises of his absolute discretion.","start":3076.754,"stop":3080.564,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3080.564,"stop":3080.824,"duration":0.26},{"text":"I understand that.","start":3080.824,"stop":3081.554,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is what -- that is the sole ground upon which the District Court and the Court of Appeals --","start":3081.554,"stop":3087.154,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean to say that --","start":3087.154,"stop":3087.844,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- founded their act.","start":3087.844,"stop":3088.214,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the argument is made and has prevailed that although the Secretary could fire out of hand, he can't devise a system by which he says, “I'm going to be bound in the future,” that's ultra vires.","start":3088.214,"stop":3098.464,"duration":10.25}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3098.464,"stop":3099.314,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'll be listening to the Government with great interest on that claim.","start":3099.314,"stop":3104.234,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we maintain that these 1951 regulations were equally violated in one of the respects which I had just mentioned to Mr. -- to you, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":3104.234,"stop":3118.974,"duration":14.74},{"text":"Another is a provision under Section 392.1 of the amended version which appears at page 75 of our appendix.","start":3118.974,"stop":3131.714,"duration":12.74},{"text":"That -- that section requires that both as to loyalty adjudications and security risk adjudications, a decision for removal of an employee shall be reached after consideration of the complete file, arguments, briefs, and testimony presented.","start":3131.714,"stop":3156.451,"duration":24.74},{"text":"Now, we submit that it can hardly be said that this requirement was met when the Secretary read and relied solely on this unlawful finding of the Loyalty Review Board while disregarding all the remainder of the record, all the testimony, including the favorable opinions of his own Loyalty Security Board.","start":3156.451,"stop":3181.998,"duration":25.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand it, however, the Government claimed that the Secretary didn't have a right to give him (Inaudible)","start":3181.998,"stop":3188.368,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct and if I may I shall come to that now.","start":3188.368,"stop":3196.088,"duration":7.72},{"text":"So, those are the two respects in which we maintain that even if they could be applied, the 1951 version of the regulations were equally violated.","start":3196.088,"stop":3206.578,"duration":10.49},{"text":"But as has been suggested, the Government maintains that these regulations, first of all, were not in terms applicable to this action.","start":3206.578,"stop":3233.175,"duration":26.6},{"text":"And they also maintained and the court below have held that even if applicable, the regulations were invalid.","start":3233.175,"stop":3243.995,"duration":10.82},{"text":"Now --","start":3243.995,"stop":3245.055,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you can say they claimed they were not applicable, didn't he --","start":3245.055,"stop":3247.519,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3247.519,"stop":3247.552,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- give notice to Service, refer to this?","start":3247.552,"stop":3251.069,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3251.069,"stop":3254.739,"duration":3.67},{"text":"As I understand the Government's position that -- that the regulations were not in terms applicable, they -- it rest on these propositions.","start":3254.739,"stop":3267.815,"duration":13.08},{"text":"First, they say that the McCarran Rider authority, this broad authority to dismiss in the absolute discretion of the Secretary, whatever he deems it in the interest of the United States, embraces cases -- this is an argument which they have developed in page 28 of their brief.","start":3267.815,"stop":3287.6,"duration":19.78},{"text":"They say, “The McCarran Rider authority embraces cases other than those of persons whose loyalty or security is doubted,” a broader category.","start":3287.6,"stop":3298.051,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Secondly, as I understand their argument, they say that the Secretary's regulations here dealt only with loyalty and security cases.","start":3298.051,"stop":3310.49,"duration":12.44},{"text":"And in purport to -- to proscribe procedures applicable to some other kind of case which he might have decided under the broad authority of -- of the Rider.","start":3310.49,"stop":3323.37,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Consequently, they say, “Since the petitioner was in fact discharged without regard to the regulation, he must have been discharged for some reason other than loyalty or security.”","start":3323.37,"stop":3338.311,"duration":14.94},{"text":"Now, of course, the trouble with this argument is that while the McCarran Rider may embrace authority to make dismissals on other than loyalty-security ground or security grounds, it certainly did embrace those grounds among others.","start":3338.311,"stop":3356.616,"duration":18.3},{"text":"Secondly, the State Department considered this legislation as it stated in the report to the Congress as an additional standard for dealing with security problem.","start":3356.616,"stop":3366.756,"duration":10.14},{"text":"This petitioner was specifically charged under the McCarran Rider with being of doubtful loyalty and a security risk.","start":3366.756,"stop":3375.51,"duration":8.75},{"text":"He was tried and he was found innocent on those charges.","start":3375.51,"stop":3380.577,"duration":5.07},{"text":"And everybody, from beginning to end, including the Loyalty Review Board on whose unlawful finding the Secretary relied solely thought they were tried and dealing with charges of loyalty and security.","start":3380.577,"stop":3398.878,"duration":18.3},{"text":"But the Government says, “Even though the Secretary held out a promise to be here,” he was free in the end to say, \"I've never intended to apply these procedures to you that I'd said I'd apply.","start":3398.878,"stop":3415.27,"duration":16.39},{"text":"I'm going to find you guilty of something other than I had charged you with and I won't even now tell you what it is.\"","start":3415.27,"stop":3427.138,"duration":11.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, assuming all that was two types of decision that that is not what he did in any event?","start":3427.138,"stop":3432.775,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":3432.775,"stop":3433.401,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That he said he discharged him because of the finding of loyalty?","start":3433.401,"stop":3436.047,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"C. Edward Rhetts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3436.047,"stop":3436.56,"duration":0.51},{"text":"And I -- I say that this is somewhat unattractive position.","start":3436.56,"stop":3440.314,"duration":3.75},{"text":"It's not the one that the Secretary adopted for himself.","start":3440.314,"stop":3444.796,"duration":4.48},{"text":"He purported, tried this man on loyalty and security grounds.","start":3444.796,"stop":3450.37,"duration":5.57},{"text":"And -- and even had he pursued this other technique, I can't believe that he could find the sanction of law.","start":3450.37,"stop":3460.319,"duration":9.95},{"text":"And so, for both of these reasons, that is because that -- well, there remains the courts the other argument that the -- the courts have found that it was not the intent of Congress that he should impose any regulations onto himself.","start":3460.319,"stop":3475.907,"duration":15.59},{"text":"And consequently, the regulations even though in terms applicable, even though the Secretary represented that they would be applied must -- may be disregarded.","start":3475.907,"stop":3487.351,"duration":11.44},{"text":"Now, we submit that this position is -- as untenable as the Government's other position for there's no shred of -- of evidence in the legislative history of the legislation to suggest that Congress ever had any such intention affirmatively to prevent the exercise of this broad discretionary authority in accordance with civilized standards.","start":3487.351,"stop":3514.982,"duration":27.63},{"text":"And indeed, there is positive evidence that the Congress by twice reenacting this legislation after receiving a report of the Secretary of State, positively approved his method of applying it because the Secretary of State has represented that he conceive the McCarran Rider to be subject to procedural limitation and advised the Congress that he had in fact promulgated procedural regulations governing his conduct, both under the McCarran Rider and under the Loyalty Executive Order.","start":3514.982,"stop":3552.683,"duration":37.7},{"text":"Consequently, we say that both for the reason that his action was arbitrary and that it was a departure from valid, applicable regulations which he imposed on himself, the decision of the Court of Appeals must be reversed.","start":3552.683,"stop":3573.183,"duration":20.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3573.183,"stop":3579.099,"duration":5.92}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  2 - 3, 1957","petitioner":"Service","respondent":"Dulles","docket":"407","citation":"354 US 363 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/363","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 17, 1957"}